(41, 37, '3', '7', 'Shanghai, China', '', '', '', 'The Shanghai vista is pure fantasy, from the endless field of high-rises cascading into the mist to the densely packed streets lined with elms and charming row houses, home to both young designers from around the country and old Shanghaiers. Filled with towering spires straight out of a sci-fi movie and majestic edifices from the colonial period, Shanghai boasts a multifaceted architectural landscape with the exhilaratingly forward-looking, the lovingly-renovated, and the still-deteriorating standing side-by-side.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	Design duo Rossana Hu and Lyndon Neri are helping change and preserve Shanghai&amp;rsquo;s design scene at the same time.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/41/shanghai_china_1.jpg_172738_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Designed by Kohn Pedersen Fox, the Shanghai World Financial Centre&amp;rsquo;s hollow apex was originally based on the Chinese concept of the Moon Gate.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;The Shanghai vista is pure fantasy, from the endless field of high-rises cascading into the mist to the densely packed streets lined with elms and charming row houses, home to both young designers from around the country and old Shanghaiers. Filled with towering spires straight out of a sci-fi movie and majestic edifices from the colonial period, Shanghai boasts a multifaceted architectural landscape with the exhilaratingly forward-looking, the lovingly-renovated, and the still-deteriorating standing side-by-side.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Shanghai is a strange, magnetic island, standing apart from the rest of China. In the early 20th period, no Asian city could claim a more diverse set of nationalities and cultural influences. Now, as financial and commercial hub of the world&amp;rsquo;s most vibrant major economy, Shanghai has reclaimed its former status as a leading cosmopolis. The vibrancy of this city of nearly 25 million people, and its unique aesthetic in China, come together in affluence and glamour, past and present.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/41/shanghai_china_2.jpg_172748_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Neri&amp;amp;Hu-designed Waterhouse boutique hotel in the Cool Docks development three linked 1930s warehouses that were in an advanced state of deterioration.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	A new visitor to the city would do well to enjoy breakfast in one of the restored classic hotels like the Waldorf Astoria or the Peace Hotel, sip a cocktail on the roof of House of Roosevelt, Glamour Bar, or the Waterhouse, or simply walk along the recently renovated Bund to concurrently imbibe the power of rising China and the romance of Shanghai. Somewhat ironically, history is better-preserved and therefore more visible here in this youngish metropolis than in a multitude of Chinese cities with pasts stretching back to antiquity. From the celebrated Hungarian architect L&amp;aacute;szl&amp;oacute; Hudec&amp;rsquo;s Park Hotel to the old HSBC Building, a massive granite and marble tribute to the once-mighty British that is now home to Shanghai Pudong Development Bank, the well-restored colonial period banks and trading houses that are now home to the city&amp;rsquo;s chicest eateries, clubs, and galleries continue to symbolise the city in the eyes of locals and foreigners.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/41/shanghai_china_3.jpg_172801_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Bon vivant and magnate Victor Sassoon&amp;rsquo;s Cathay Hotel, once the most opulent hotel in Asia and considered one of the most perfect examples of Art Deco architecture, was renamed Peace Hotel after Liberation and has now been lovingly renovated by the Fairmont Group. Every inch of the property has a story.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	But sometimes it seems the grand Bund structures are recommissioned only to provide a better point from which to observe towering Lujiazui, the centrepiece of Pudong District&amp;rsquo;s Finance and Trade Zone. In what only 20 years ago was a swamp stand the bottle-opener-shaped Shanghai World Financial Centre at 492m and the Skidmore, Owings &amp;amp; Merrilldesigned Jinmao Tower at 421m, which many architects say blends a pagoda-like design with Shanghai&amp;rsquo;s Art Deco past. Ready to dwarf both in 2014 is the Shanghai Tower, which at 632m will be yet another vertical symbol of Shanghai&amp;rsquo;s ascent.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Fusing East and West and new and old are at the core of Shanghai&amp;rsquo;s architectural identity and urban layout. Most omnipresent is the shikumen housing, which unites European row house architecture with the Chinese courtyard to create an entirely Shanghaiese synthesis. One goal for local designers and architects is creating a new aesthetic language that reflects and builds upon the city&amp;rsquo;s unique identity.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/41/shanghai_china_4.jpg_172813_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Perhaps the culmination of the Bund&amp;rsquo;s return to glamour, the best views of futuristic Pudong and Shanghai&amp;rsquo;s best wine selection are both found here.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Perhaps the most well-known locally based team committed to building design in the city is husband and wife Rossana Hu and Lyndon Neri. In Shanghai since 2001, Neri has conceptualised some of the most impressive revitalisations of historic buildings the city has seen. Bund 3, now home to such culinary diamonds as Jean Georges and New Heights, as well as the Whampoa Cub Beijing, was the work of the pair while they were still working for American firm Michael Graves. The Waterhouse boutique hotel, completed last year, showcases a vision for how traditional modes of Shanghai living can be subtly but meaningfully incorporated in modern design. Their own villa is also a model for renovations in the French Concession. Beyond architecture, the pair created Neri&amp;amp;Hu, now one of the leading product design brands in China, and opened Design Republic, which has brought the best of international design to Shanghai consumers since 2007. These two have been an important part of Shanghai&amp;rsquo;s growth as a design city, and have influenced its aesthetic identity.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Dwell Asia: Some younger local architects claim developers only look backwards and lack imagination and courage. From an aesthetic perspective, is Shanghai too hooked on its past?&amp;nbsp; Do new buildings try too hard to mimic or fit in with that past?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Unfortunately, the situation is quite the opposite. The problem with developers and architects in Shanghai is that they try to outdo one another with the tallest, the biggest, the most complex and in general the most in everything without much thought to context or history. There are many beautiful Art Deco buildings and we wish Shanghai would try to keep most of it and not be like Hong Kong where the majority of significant older buildings are demolished to make way for taller and more commercially lucrative new buildings. The fabric of some of the, significant lane houses in Shanghai is no longer in existence.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/41/shanghai_china_5.jpg_172825_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Andy Warhol meets the Yucatan in Shanghai&amp;rsquo;s most famous serial restaurateur David Laris&amp;rsquo; dazzling Mexican restaurant in the French Concession&amp;rsquo;s newest urban renewal zone, Sinan Mansions.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What about efforts to give the 1920s, 1930s city a new life? Is preservation being done right and is it done enough? What are the best examples?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	A few of the lane houses have been given new life. Is it done enough? Definitely not, and we believe significant improvements can be made. Of course, in many cases malls and ugly office buildings have simply replaced lovely older neighbourhoods that were demolished. Some of the better examples are in the Bund and French Concession. Among the best older structures that have been given new life or recently refurbished are the Peace Hotel, Hengshan church, the Paramount building, Waldorf Astoria on the Bund, Astor Place, buildings on Huashan and Wukang Roads and many more.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Is the Waterhouse being imitated in Shanghai? Do you hope that it could inspire similar renovations in the city?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	We would not know for now, but we are sure there are people who are interested in the approach we took. We definitely would like people to look at renovation in a fresh way.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Does Shanghai have an advantage over other Chinese cities from an&amp;nbsp;urban planning perspective?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Yes, because it is a very dense city and it is growing at a rapid pace. People are not afraid to experiment.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Are other cities &amp;ndash; particularly in the developing world &amp;ndash; learning from Shanghai? What should they&amp;nbsp; imitate and what should be avoided?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Developing cities can learn from some of Shanghai&amp;rsquo;s more sensitive insertions to older neighbourhoods, and the adaptive reuse of older structures. They should definitely avoid the massive demolition that destroyed some of the city fabric. Non-elites &amp;ndash; the majority of Shanghaiers &amp;ndash; have benefited a great deal from improvements in the mass-transit system. The subway is a lot better after the Expo and there are many more parks all over the city.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What are some examples of urban development projects that are making Shanghai feel like more of a cultural city?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The renovated Bund, the French Concession and many other new lifestyle redevelopment projects like Sinan Mansion, Ferguson Lane and Surpass Court. The new area in Jingan, south of the main shopping area in Nanjing Road is also interesting. We like Ferguson Lane, which is a typical four-storey non descript building hidden behind a series of lane houses that was renovated with the intention of bringing life deep into the lane houses. The development is comprised of small boutique retail stores and a number of restaurants on the ground floor with office space rented for creative agencies.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Has Shanghai found a distinct visual language?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Shanghai is in the process of finding its identity. It is less chaotic compared to 15 years ago but there are still many different visual languages. The Bund and the French Concession have a more cohesive visual identity, but this is based on older buildings.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Laszlo Hudec is perhaps the architectural father of Shanghai &amp;ndash; name three other architects visitors should know?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Ma Qing-yun, Zhu Xiao-feng and (obviously) Neri and Hu. Have a look at the Father&amp;rsquo;s House in Xian and Zone for High Education Park in Zhejiang by Ma, and the Zhujiajiao Museum of Humanities and Arts and Dashawan Beach Facilities at Liandao Island by Zhu. The Black Box and Waterhouse are two of our best-known projects in Shanghai.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Nels Frye', '2012-02-28', '17:18:41', '2012-02-24', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '17:24', '201202241724', '41_small__173711_vino_cms_.jpg', '41_medium__173711_vino_cms_.jpg', '41_big__173711_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 50, 1, 1, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-3-7-2012-02-27/', 'shanghai--china.html', '', '', 41, ''),
(28, 25, '2', '5', 'Natural Power', '', '', '', 'An eco-home in Singapore sa ves dollars and makes sense with a sustainable design typology tailored to the tropical climate.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;span style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Photos by &lt;strong&gt;Lim Shiang Han and Ng Ken Liong&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Project:&lt;strong&gt; 36 BTrd&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Architect: &lt;strong&gt;Jaye Tan Jia Yee, DP Architects&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Location:&lt;strong&gt; Singapore&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;An eco-home in Singapore sa ves dollars and makes sense with a sustainable design typology tailored to the tropical climate.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/28/natural_power_1.jpg_145429_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Common living areas, shared by Ong and his tenants, are laid out in open plan on the ground floor.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	If there were such a thing as a statement piece in architecture, it would be the house at 36 Boon Teck Road, Singapore. This is a house that has its neighbours talking, interested tenants knocking, intrigued passers-by stopping in their tracks, and the most curious ones stepping up to ask, &amp;ldquo;Can I come in to look at your house?&amp;rdquo; And although manym people might find this level of interest in their home overwhelming, it was everything homeowner Daniel Ong and architect Jaye Tan hoped for.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	One and a half years ago, Ong and Tan teamed up to build what is now Singapore&amp;rsquo;s first landed home property to earn the Green Mark Platinum Award &amp;ndash; a recognition conferred by the Building and Construction Authority on the best examples of ecobuildings in the country. But the duo&amp;rsquo;s achievement is beyond personal. &amp;ldquo;The whole idea we had was not just to build a sustainable house, but also one that promotes green home designs,&amp;rdquo; says Ong. &amp;ldquo;Jaye heads the environment design team at DP Architects, so this is very much a kind of flagship home DP Architects wanted to use in showcasing how far they can push the envelope on sustainable design in the residential context. The house is a shout-out, a way to create awareness and we knew we really needed to obtain something quite different. We really needed to stand out.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/28/natural_power_2.jpg_145447_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The random brick protrusions on the wall become ideal spots for tealights on evenings when ambient lighting is in order&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Stand out it does. Sandwiched in a row of interterrace units, the three-storey building stands completely see-through from the front, wall-less, with only its top half finned by a steel curtain &amp;ndash; a jarring juxtaposition to the concrete mass of houses left and right of it. &amp;ldquo;We elevated the first storey so that from the street, the living area coincides with the eye level and passers-by can see through the entire house, from the garage, the open kitchen and sitting area, all the way back to the dining and the back porch with the nice, vertical green wall,&amp;rdquo; explains Ong.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Look into the foliage-fringed house and the property does remind you of a jungle-themed caf&amp;eacute; &amp;ndash; except there is no tromp l&amp;rsquo;oeil on the walls, but a real eco-system living in the building. Trees are actually brought into the house and on the aforementioned vertical green wall, real plants thrive (or die, as Daniel confesses: &amp;ldquo;That green wall is still something of a test bed&amp;rdquo;). Indeed, the house has become an experiment in eco-living and biodiversity; even a bat that has made a home on the second level. But the house mostly lures people in. First it was the neighbours, but before long, the media spread the word beyond the immediate vicinity. &amp;ldquo;When the first story went out in the local papers, many would-be homeowners came to see us,&amp;rdquo; says Ong. &amp;ldquo;We were more than happy to share our story, pass on contacts, provide some consultation. Many of them told us how they were really interested but thought it would be beyond their means to live this way. I tell them it&amp;rsquo;s not true. Look at me, I am not a multi millionaire.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/28/natural_power_3.jpg_145506_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;A centrally-located stairwell helps to bring more light into the elongated house.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Not that Ong, a private wealth management consultant, is suggesting that green technology is dirt cheap. To start, there are the rooftop photovoltaic panels that generate power for a Hybrid DC air-conditioner, solar thermal collectors that harness energy for a DC water heater, and a solar charger placed outside of his gate for passers-by to charge their electric bikes or their mobile devices (another&amp;nbsp; &amp;ldquo;green outreach&amp;rdquo; feature). The setup can be elaborate and these contraptions come at a premium. &amp;ldquo;But this stuff lasts a long time, you know, all our satellites, all our buggies on Mars run on solar panels. They last 70, 100 years, a really long time,&amp;rdquo; Ong explains, as we peer up the central volume to marvel at the wonders of the energy machine set up above. Only 40 percent of the front roof portion is clad in photovoltaic cells, so daylight still filters though, reducing the need for artificial lighting through the elongated span of the house.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;I have limited resources so I find ways to build conservatively without spending too much,&amp;rdquo; says Ong. The house is built on a bare steel framework with lightweight metal composite floors, its sidewalls are made of bricks to minimise concrete usage (&amp;ldquo;Concrete is not harmful, but the process of making it is&amp;rdquo;), and furniture and flooring come from reclaimed timber.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/28/natural_power_4.jpg_145528_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ong&amp;rsquo;s own space spans the entire depth of the house on the second level and is built without partitioning walls. Instead, sliding panels are used to optimise cross ventilation.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The house also makes clever use of passive design. Balconies and overhangs provide natural sun-shading. Sliding panes (replacing walls) also optimise airflow and encourage natural cross ventilation. &amp;ldquo;And what is really interesting is that our photovoltaic cells heat up very hot, but this actually creates a stack effect in the central stairwell, and in turn creates more draft in the house,&amp;rdquo; Ong explains proudly. What is cooler though, is how the financial-savvy owner also makes sure that the house stays sustainable economically.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;We used steel in the first place because we wanted to reduce concrete use, but steel is about 20 percent more expensive than concrete. Furthermore, steel prices were very high at that time we built. I knew that cost was the greatest challenge here, so to offset the upfront investment, I designed the house so that the whole third floor can be let out,&amp;rdquo; Ong explains. The kitchen (a programme detail pushed to the side of the house so the living space is enlarged) is also rented out for cooking classes. And to keep running costs low, energy savings are maximised even within the slim space of the kitchen. &amp;ldquo;We installed these glass partitions here so that when, for example, we make pastries, we can just close off a small portion of the kitchen and turn on the air-conditioner.&amp;rdquo; The electric bills come to about two hundred Singapore dollars &amp;ndash; an admirable figure for a house accommodating four people and a rather heavy-duty kitchen. But what is most impressive about this house is not how much it saves in cents and dollars, but how it has let so many see that our power meters at home can, with a little investment in design planning, be actually made to run backwards. And this, in our energy crisis-stricken world, is an affirmative and somewhat thrilling demonstration of the power of design and technology.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Yvonne Xu', '2012-02-28', '14:16:21', '2012-02-24', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '14:28', '201202241428', '28_small__141621_vino_cms_.jpg', '28_medium__141621_vino_cms_.jpg', '28_big__141621_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 18, 1, 0, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-2-5-2012-02-28/', 'natural-power.html', '', '', 28, ''),
