(40, 37, '3', '7', 'Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam', '', '', '', 'In The City Formerly Known As Saigon, adventurous new towers play off against Art Deco treasures, magnificent French colonial buildings and traditional Chinese temples. With renowned international architects contributing to modern urban developments and local firms establishing a post-war vernacular, Ho Chi Minh City has the energy of a city finding its unique voice in design.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;span style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Photos by &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Kevin German&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;In The City Formerly Known As Saigon, adventurous new towers play off against Art Deco treasures, magnificent French colonial buildings and traditional Chinese temples. With renowned international architects contributing to modern urban developments and local firms establishing a post-war vernacular, Ho Chi Minh City has the energy of a city finding its unique voice in design.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Ho Chi Minh City (HCMC) may not be the political capital of Vietnam, but it&amp;rsquo;s the country&amp;rsquo;s business hub and its leading international city. The frenetic rush is encapsulating; every treelined road is awash with motorbikes snaking around an ever-increasing number of cars, including more Bentleys than you&amp;rsquo;re likely to encounter in London&amp;rsquo;s Mayfair.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The city&amp;rsquo;s architecture reflects Vietnam&amp;rsquo;s tumultuous past. Pagodas and temples sit alongside colonial townhouses, Art Deco apartment nblocks and grand Constructionist pieces, while the Soviet housing projects are enough to make Balkans natives feel right at home. Its unique brand of Art Deco &amp;ndash; simplified, less formal and heavier than Western examples &amp;ndash; arrived late, at the end of the 1940s and, for some, it gives the city its identity.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/40/ho_chi_minh_city_1.jpg_162232_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Bitexco Financial Tower, currently the 124th tallest building in the world, was completed in October 2010 by US-based architecture firm Carlos Zapata Studio.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	HCMC remains a city of change. Look skyward and the number of cranes is testament to colossal development. Tired-eyed residents bemoan that as soon as the drilling stops in one direction, it starts again in another. Whole new cities within a city are being constructed. Rising from its heart, the 68-floor Bitexco Tower stands as a new landmark and fitting monument to grand intentions.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Development here, much like in Bangkok, is sporadic and sometimes haphazard: skyscrapers are thrown up on six-metre-wide streets. All this comes at a price. The loss of Art Deco and colonial era buildings is muchlamented and there is some fear that the architectural soul of HCMC is being lost in the rush to catch up with its neighbours.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Despite this, HCMC remains a city that sucks people in. Developers are increasingly realising the value of merging Vietnamese cultural elements with contemporary design and the city is developing a buzz and an international feel.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Old buildings may disappear, but the way of life that gives HCMC its character ploughs on regardless. Suited and booted stock exchange workers still pull up shin-high plastic stools at 10-cent iced tea stands, while women wearing conical hats and shouldering mobile soup kitchens amble past. England&amp;rsquo;s David Hodkinson and Frenchman Luc Lejeune founded their progressive architecture firm, Noor Architects, in HCMC over a decade ago. They&amp;rsquo;ve witnessed many changes over the last ten years while doing much to stamp their mark on the city. Here, they give us an overview of their adopted home&amp;rsquo;s modern face.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/40/ho_chi_minh_city_2.jpg_162302_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Built in 1968, the General Sciences Library has been at the heart of promoting Vietnamese culture, in a uniquely Constructivist-style building&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What are the architectural highlights of your city?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	LL: It&amp;rsquo;s the older buildings that we admire. The General Sciences Library (69 Ly Tu Trong Street) is a wonderful Constructivist building and then there are the last remaining Art Deco apartments along Dong Khoi. Sadly the Mondial Building, which I loved, has gone and others I particularly like are likely to follow it. So much has been lost. The post-war 1950s apartment blocks at the beginning of Le Duan and on Tran Quoc Thao are also favorites.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;To what extent do you think HCMC has a distinctive architectural style?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	LL: Perhaps less now than in the past. The buildings I mention are from a time when the city definitely had its own style. HCMC was an outpost and that lead to some interesting results and a very unique style, which spread out across Indochina. A lot of HCMCstyle Deco can be found in Phnom Penh but, paradoxically, there is much less in Hanoi. In Europe it would have been viewed as second class, but here it&amp;rsquo;s very appealing.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/40/ho_chi_minh_city_3.jpg_162314_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Amber Room is a New York-style lounge bar, catering to HCMC&amp;rsquo;s&amp;nbsp;increasingly designconscious drinkers.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Height appears to be all-important in HCMC, with the new Bitexco Tower setting the standard &amp;ndash; it is winning plaudits left right and centre. What are your thoughts?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	DH: It&amp;rsquo;s true &amp;ndash; I&amp;rsquo;ve never heard anyone say anything negative about it. It&amp;rsquo;s a very daring piece of architecture for HCMC. It would be totally at home in Dubai. When I first saw the specifications, I thought it was crazy. It&amp;rsquo;s so Dubai, in fact, it almost looks like it has been copied from something there. But then we saw it going up and it was handled so professionally. It&amp;rsquo;s become a landmark.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;So, despite its location among the old buildings you admire, this one has earned its place. Would the city benefit from more high-rise development?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	DH: Well, the contrast they have achieved with the old buildings works extremely well. It&amp;rsquo;s a very distinctive design and it adds to the area. I truly admire the investors for taking such a huge risk. As for more buildings, yes, let&amp;rsquo;s have more bold designs and give the residents something to look at, but not in the same area &amp;ndash; across the river in Thu Tiem, so we keep what we have left. We don&amp;rsquo;t want to follow Hong Kong, which has lost almost all of its fantastic old buildings.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;With an increasing number of architects moving in and building sites appearing on a daily basis, these must be exciting times.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	LL: Yes, there&amp;rsquo;s a huge amount of energy in the city &amp;ndash; a colossal amount of development and a huge enthusiasm. There&amp;rsquo;s a definite sense of anarchy in the way it&amp;rsquo;s happening, which leads to some good experimental projects and some that are, well, less than perfect. For many developers with private money it&amp;rsquo;s all about show &amp;ndash; they decide they want a building in the shape of a lotus, someone acquiesces, and it&amp;rsquo;s built in a very whimsical way leading to different levels of dreadfulness. Ho Chi Minh is a very mixed bag.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/40/ho_chi_minh_city_4.jpg_162335_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;L&amp;rsquo;Usine is a contemporary art gallery, fashion boutique and caf&amp;eacute; rolled into one in a restored French colonial building.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;How successful are the new largescale communities such as Phan My Hung (Saigon South), which have been built in response to the city&amp;rsquo;s ballooning population?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	DH: Phan My Hung works. It fulfils people&amp;rsquo;s ideals for living outside of the main city. It gives people an escape. It was extremely well designed and planned by architects from America and Japan. In just ten years they&amp;rsquo;ve utterly transformed an area. They&amp;rsquo;ve taken it from zero, a wasteland, and created a sense of community. It&amp;rsquo;s a successful suburbia. That&amp;rsquo;s what can be achieved under one investor who has clear vision.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;But along with the new communities and ever-taller apartment blocks come more cars and more pressure on public systems, right?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	DH: People here held similar concerns to those of Hanoians a few years ago. Today, people are just getting on with it and adapting to the city&amp;rsquo;s issues. We&amp;rsquo;re past the point of concern. I know some people who have cars but&amp;nbsp; they&amp;rsquo;ve gone back to motorbikes &amp;ndash; two wheels work here, not four. HCMC was designed for 400,000 people and now contains around 5,000,000. The development of Thu Thiem, HCMC&amp;rsquo;s own Pudong, will ease the strain by creating a new modern city on the opposite banks of the Saigon River.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;To what extent does HCMC capitalise on its riverfront location?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	LL: The river will one day play a much more important role for tourism and movement around the city. When the banks of District One and opposite are developed, the river will open up to the people &amp;ndash; an exciting development, as it will affect the city in so many ways. Imagine restaurants, cafes, bars, parks, artworks and skate parks bringing colour to the riverfront. That will be fantastic.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'David Lloyd Son', '2012-03-01', '16:20:46', '2012-02-24', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '16:14', '201202241614', '40_small__155353_vino_cms_.jpg', '40_medium__162046_vino_cms_.png', '40_big__162046_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 28, 1, 1, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-3-7-2012-03-01/', 'ho-chi-minh-city--vietnam.html', '', '', 40, ''),
(4, 10, '1', '0', 'Fragmanted Cabinets 01', '', '', '', 'Nesting tables â€“ sure, weâ€™ve seen that, but nesting storage? A Singapore-London duo has designed a set of elasticised cabinets that straddle each other in a colourful trio.', '', '&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Lanzavecchia and Wai&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	For more info:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://lanzavecchia-wai.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;lanzavecchia-wai.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Nesting tables &amp;ndash; sure, we&amp;rsquo;ve seen that, but nesting storage? A Singapore-London duo has designed a set of elasticised cabinets that straddle each other in a colourful trio.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-24', '09:44:29', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '09:58', '201202090958', '4_small__163825_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '4_big__163825_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 16, 1, 0, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-1-2-2012-02-10/', 'fragmanted-cabinets-01.html', '', '', 4, ''),
(5, 10, '1', '0', 'Phul Patti Chair', '', '', '', '', '', '&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Mann Singh&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	For more info:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://chairmann.blogspot.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;chairmann.blogspot.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-24', '09:44:22', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '09:59', '201202090959', '5_small__163759_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '5_big__163759_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 26, 1, 0, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-1-2-2012-02-10/', 'phul-patti-chair.html', '', '', 5, ''),
(15, 26, '2', '6', 'BUSH BABY', '', '', '', 'Good architecture should stand the test of time, and this holiday home is already proving to be one for the generations.', '', '&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n		Project: &lt;strong&gt;Foxground House&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n	&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n		Architect: &lt;strong&gt;Louise Nettleton Architects&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n	&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n		Location:&lt;strong&gt; Rural New South Wales,&amp;nbsp;Australia&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n	&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n		&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nettletonarchitect.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;nettletonarchitect.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Good architecture should stand the test of time, and this holiday home is already proving to be one for the generations.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n		Designed for an octogenarian who&amp;nbsp;wanted a holiday escape that would be&amp;nbsp;a tribute to his late wife and a legacy for&amp;nbsp;his children and grandchildren, the Foxground&amp;nbsp;House has a simple but effective&amp;nbsp;layout that opens up as a multi-family&amp;nbsp;retreat, and locks down for safe-keeping&amp;nbsp;during its empty periods. Corrugated&amp;nbsp;iron &amp;ndash; a classic material in the Australian&amp;nbsp;architectural vernacular &amp;ndash; is used for&amp;nbsp;roofing and cladding, with a dynamically&amp;nbsp;tilted roof that opens one side of the&amp;nbsp;building to lush bush views, improves&amp;nbsp;cross-ventilation and reflects light in the&amp;nbsp;summer. The original owner passed on&amp;nbsp;before he saw his vision come to fruition,&amp;nbsp;but it&amp;rsquo;s now being enjoyed by his offspring&amp;nbsp;&amp;ndash; and theirs &amp;ndash; just as he hoped it would be. Good on ya, mate, we say.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-28', '16:47:30', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:20', '201202091020', '15_small__094821_vino_cms_.jpg', '15_medium__094821_vino_cms_.png', '15_big__094821_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 54, 1, 1, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-2-6-2012-02-27/', 'bush-baby.html', '', '', 15, ''),
(16, 26, '2', '6', 'BLOW UP', '', '', '', 'Tradition and innovation harmoniously coincide in a home extension that reflects well on its designers.', '', '&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Project: &lt;strong&gt;Hutong Bubble&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Location: &lt;strong&gt;Beijing, China&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Architect: &lt;strong&gt;MAD Architects&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;a href=&quot;http://i-mad.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;i-mad.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Tradition and innovation harmoniously coincide in a home extension that reflects well on its designers.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	As the pace of urban development picks up throughout China, old Beijing&amp;rsquo;s communal courtyard homes or hutongs are due for much-needed restoration. As a part of a residential development concept to preserve traditional homes, MAD, a Beijing architecture firm, came up with the idea of Hutong Bubbles: a chromed, organic home extension that expands space and &amp;ndash; over time &amp;ndash; will become an iconic feature of the city. This one, the first, houses a toilet and stairwell that provides access to the roof terrace. As the old neighbourhood is reflected in the mirrored surface of the futuristic bubbles, old and new are literally drawn together.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Olivia Hidajat', '2012-02-28', '16:43:58', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:23', '201202091023', '16_small__093134_vino_cms_.jpg', '16_medium__093134_vino_cms_.png', '16_big__093134_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 72, 1, 1, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-2-6-2012-02-27/', 'blow-up.html', '', '', 16, ''),
(17, 612, '6', '12', 'SKIN TREATMENT', '', '', '', 'For this sprawling home in Singapore, Aamer Architects were asked to accommodate three generations of family, a steeply undulating site, and a strict requirement that the home align with feng shui principles.', '', '&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	For this sprawling home in Singapore, Aamer Architects were asked to accommodate three generations of family, a steeply undulating site, and a strict requirement that the home align with feng shui principles. Undaunted, they tackled the challenge with aplomb. Spatially, the home was massed into three areas &amp;ndash; the sleeping, entertainment and recreation zones &amp;ndash; joined by a central spine and core that contained the living rooms. According to feng shui principles, the main spaces needed to open up towards the west, so the communal areas were set toward the front of the house, and the sleeping areas to the back. Finally, each member of the family had a set of feng shui-approved colours, which were integrated into the material and tonal palette of the different interior spaces.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	To bring it all together, Aamer Architects conceived a striking exterior timber &amp;lsquo;skin&amp;rsquo; that wraps around the central spaces of the house, uniting the regions conceptually while acting as a sun-shading element and insulation. The herringbone detailing is made from a tropical &amp;lsquo;iron wood&amp;rsquo; and creates a cavity layer over the concrete, cooling the house. Texturally and colourwise, the surface works harmoniously with the feng shui guidelines. Now that&amp;rsquo;s a wrap!&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-28', '10:07:55', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:50', '201202091050', '17_small__100755_vino_cms_.jpg', '17_medium__100755_vino_cms_.jpg', '17_big__100755_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 54, 1, 0, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-6-12-2012-02-28/', 'skin-treatment.html', '', '', 17, ''),
(18, 612, '6', '12', 'FLIGHT OF FANCY', '', '', '', 'In the heart of a residential concrete bunker in Tokyo, a lacelike staircase unfurls to bring light and air into the home.', '', '&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;In the heart of a residential concrete bunker in Tokyo, a lacelike staircase unfurls to bring light and air into the home.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Along with halls, staircases are often the most neglected area of the house when it comes to engaging design, existing as little more than conduits to help you get where you&amp;rsquo;re going as quickly as possible. But in this house, in the Minami Aoyama district of Tokyo, the octagonal stairwell is an enchanting place of shafted light and secret glimpses into the different levels of the house. Architect Takeshi Hirobe says the stair operates as an abstract contrast to the &amp;lsquo;reality&amp;rsquo; of the living spaces, and also plays a major structural role in the house. Reinforced glass treads allow light from the skylight to penetrate right through the four levels of the house, while the white-painted steel framework of the stairs looks like a spiderweb from the ground. Round holes of differing sizes peep through the concrete walls, maintaining a connection to the other parts of the house. Visitors who linger to enjoy the experience might not get where they&amp;rsquo;re going very fast &amp;ndash; but it&amp;rsquo;s the journey, not the destination, that counts, &lt;i&gt;desu ne&lt;/i&gt;?&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-28', '10:01:23', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:51', '201202091051', '18_small__100123_vino_cms_.jpg', '18_medium__100123_vino_cms_.jpg', '18_big__100123_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 36, 1, 0, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-6-12-2012-02-28/', 'flight-of-fancy.html', '', '', 18, ''),
(21, 11, '1', '1', 'Vase Act', '', '', '', 'Nothing gives a city home a burst of nature faster than a beautiful vase filled with flowers.', '', '&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;Story by Melinda Williams&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;Photos by Evie Mackay&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;Nothing gives a city home a burst of nature faster than a beautiful vase filled with flowers.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	As a functional objext, the vase has a simple task: hold water and flowers, but as a form, it has long been used as an object of art, from extravagant Jomon earthenware to beautifully decorated and glazed Tang Dynasty pieces. Modern designer vases bring function and form together in an elegantly minimal way &amp;ndash; here, we look at some of the best from around the world.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;SAVOY VASE&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Alvar Aalto &amp;amp; Aino Marsio for iittala&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 313&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Pros: Probably the most famous designer vase in the world, this much-loved undulating design comes in a full range of colours, and even in opaque duo-tone, to fit any setting.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Cons: Unless it&amp;rsquo;s fully packed with clean-stemmed blooms like tulips, the vase isn&amp;rsquo;t actually a great shape for displaying flowers. Some people use it as a small fishbowl instead, or just let the shape speak for itself.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;RIMINI BLU VASE&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Aldo Londi for Bitossi Ceramiche&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 121&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Pros: Originally created in the 1950s, these hand-made vases, with their blue-green glazing reminiscent of the Mediterranean Sea, were re-issued starting in 2006, making them available to a wider audience.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Cons: While the vases themselves are pretty solid the glaze is pretty fragile &amp;ndash; one little bump can chip it &amp;ndash; so keep these on a stable surface far from grabby little hands.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;ORB VASE&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Peter Collis&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 165&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Pros: The bright red crackle glaze (inspired by traditional Chinese techniques) and unusual shape are real eye-catchers even without flowers &amp;ndash; this is more an art piece than a functional vase.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Cons: The elegant line of the neck of the vase is so fine that it&amp;rsquo;s impossible to fit more than the finest of stems into it. Perhaps just a single cloud of Baby&amp;rsquo;s Breath?&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;FASETT FLOWER VESSEL&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Andrea Shaw for Stampel&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 58&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Pros: Handmade from postmanufacture timber waste with a soy wax finish inside, these charming vases are ecological and look great as a collection.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Cons: While the natural imperfections of the wood are part of the vase&amp;rsquo;s charm, slightly more attention to finish would make the final product even more attractive.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;WELD VASE&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Phil Cuttance&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 220&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Pros: Surprisingly lightweight and able to take a few knocks, this is a great vase for a home with kids. The height and mouth width are great for many types of flower.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Cons: The painstaking handassembly process of the vases means that, despite being plastic, they come in at the high end of the price scale for our selection.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;BOWL VASE&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Sfera&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 254&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Pros: Hand-blown by Japanese artisans, these simple but beautiful vases have a wide mouth ideal for displaying water lilies or short-stemmed flowers like magnolias.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Cons: The glass is finely blown and delicate, so unlike the more substantial Savoy Vase, this one won&amp;rsquo;t withstand any knocks.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;VASE&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Gidon Bing&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 135&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Pros: Auckland-based sculptor Gidon Bing uses Japanese and Korean ceramic glazing techniques on his small but perfectly formed vases. This one is just right for a small posy.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Cons: Hand-made by the artist himself, these vases are in pretty short supply. You might be waiting a while for delivery.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;VAASE&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Marc Pascal&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 396&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Pros: Inspired by deep-sea coral, this vase is an unusual and striking way to display flowers or branches in a minimal way (even just one looks wonderful).&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Cons: The six-stem concept makes it pretty hard to display more than, well, six flowers without the display looking cluttered. This one tops out our price list at almost SG$400.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-28', '15:53:51', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '16:46', '201202091646', '21_small__155351_vino_cms_.jpg', '21_medium__155351_vino_cms_.jpg', '21_big__155351_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 50, 1, 0, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-1-1-2012-02-28/', 'vase-act.html', '', '', 18, ''),
(19, 12, '1', '2', 'Tetrabox Lamp', '', '', '', 'Assembled origami-style from hundreds of recycled drink cartons, this geometric light by Malaysian designer Ed Chew can be made at home via online instructions (and patience).', '', '&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Edward Chew&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	For more info:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://edchew.my/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;edchew.my&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Assembled origami-style from hundreds of recycled drink cartons, this geometric light by Malaysian designer Ed Chew can be made at home via online instructions (and patience).&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-24', '09:43:36', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '11:33', '201202091133', '19_small__163328_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '19_big__163328_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 32, 1, 0, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-1-2-2012-02-10/', 'tetrabox-lamp.html', '', '', 19, ''),
(26, 25, '2', '5', 'Modern Family', '', '', '', 'An airy, modern house built for one in Bangkok is no lonesome home â€“ itâ€™s closely linked to family, both by location and design.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Photos&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt; by Jirasak Thongyuak&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Feature production&lt;/strong&gt; by Nuanwan Supertpanich&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Project:&lt;/strong&gt; Tantivit House&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Architect:&lt;/strong&gt; Arsom Silp&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Location:&lt;/strong&gt; Bangkok, Thailand&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;An airy, modern house built for one in Bangkok is no lonesome home &amp;ndash; it&amp;rsquo;s closely linked to family, both by location and design.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/26/modern_family_1.jpg_115407_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The foyer of the house does double-duty as a conversation spot, away from the media den behind.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Ten years spent living and working in the United States sent Atijnuj Tantivit home to Thailand with more than just a perfect command of the English language. While living in America, the contemporary jeweller, who also runs Atta Gallery, Thailand&amp;rsquo;s first gallery specialising in contemporary jewellery, developed a love for modernist architecture that inspired the design of her own home in Bangkok. &amp;ldquo;When I was overseas, I used to live in a house like a long box, with easy access to all the rooms. That inspired me to choose this kind of design and the convenience it had to offer,&amp;rdquo; she says. Tantivit, known as Atty to her friends and family, says she offered the architecture firm a very clear brief. &amp;ldquo;I think I was a pretty difficult client, because I&amp;rsquo;m a designer myself,&amp;rdquo; she acknowledges with a laugh. &amp;ldquo;I had an opinion on everything.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Tantivit&amp;rsquo;s land, a 100-square-wah (400sqm) section in Bangkok Metropolis, was a gift from her parents. It&amp;rsquo;s a true family neighbourhood, with her parents, brothers, grandmother and sundry aunts, uncles and cousins all housed on adjacent properties. Although her parents have more traditional architectural tastes than Tantivit does, she retained the same architects, from Arsom Silp Institute of the Arts, to design her home. Given that her home is located as part of a communal landscape, she and her parents wanted some harmony to exist between the old and the new. A walkway links the two residences, and the use of water features and garden designs were incorporated into a master plan to create a visually unified landscape and a crisp, cool atmosphere. &amp;ldquo;I always wanted a house with a pool,&amp;rdquo; says Tantivit. &amp;ldquo;I was so used to living in mom and dad&amp;rsquo;s old house, which has a pool inside. I like it because water makes the house cooler, and there&amp;rsquo;s nothing like the sound of water.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/26/modern_family_2.jpg_115454_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Tantivit often works from her kitchen, which can be closed off for easy airconditioning &amp;ndash; and lets her keep an eye out for the arrival of visitors.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Entering the property from the street through a large swivel door, visitors cross under a circular skylight and across an open wooden bridge bordered on one side by a waterfall pool and by on the other by an oversize Jacuzzi that sees plenty of use during parties. The house itself, a two-level, monoblock dwelling with a swooping &amp;lsquo;floating&amp;rsquo; roofline, has a white-painted concrete plaster finish outside, and exposed concrete wall finish within. The exterior design is clean and modern, a blend of masculinity, which is reflected in the choice of such materials as steel, wood, and concrete; and femininity in the forms of curving furniture, piles of pillows and exuberant use of colour. &amp;ldquo;Come to think of it, a house is like the kind of work we do every day,&amp;rdquo; Tantivit suggests. &amp;ldquo;Much of it comes in geometric shapes. It may sport a robust appearance, but deep down there is something soft to the touch and pleasing to the mind. It&amp;rsquo;s all about combining those qualities.&amp;rdquo; Her space also places an emphasis on simplicity, easy care, and flexibility to implement change; she likes to let the d&amp;eacute;cor reveal her current feelings and vision.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/26/modern_family_3.jpg_115519_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Blue mosaic tiles create a feature wall in the master bathroom.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	From the central entrance atrium the floor plan is laid out to create an airy interior. All the main living spaces are accessible from the centre point &amp;ndash; living room, dining room, kitchen, guest bathroom, the staircase that leads to the second floor, and Tantivit&amp;rsquo;s cultivated cactus garden. Although cacti are popular collectible plants in Thailand, they&amp;rsquo;re not naturally inclined to the climate. &amp;ldquo;I had to put a roof on the garden, because the cactuses were getting too much rain,&amp;rdquo; she admits.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	A central staircase made of steel and concrete rises to the second level above a &amp;lsquo;rug&amp;rsquo; of artificial grass that adds levity to the space and helps blur the difference between indoor and out. Upstairs, all the rooms on the second floor are accessible from the long central corridor, which branches off on one side to create an observation deck-style footbridge over the foyer, and connects to an outdoor terrace. Bedroom walls were painted white or off-white to create a relaxed atmosphere, except in Tantivit&amp;rsquo;s office and workroom, which feature a lively leaf-print wallpaper and cool blue-painted walls respectively.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/26/modern_family_4.jpg_115641_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The walk-in wardrobe and workroom&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Throughout the house, a recurrent motif is that of the circle, or bubble. Round skylights and peepholes let in light, wool-covered Swiss balls dot the d&amp;eacute;cor, and from the second storey, a yellow sculpture of a rabbit pokes its nose through a hole in a built-in display shelf that looks down to the entrance foyer. It&amp;rsquo;s a deliberate reference to her work, says Tantivit. &amp;ldquo;A lot of my jewellery is based around circles and spheres, so it made sense to bring that shape into my house.&amp;rdquo; As a designer herself, Tantivit also makes a point of collecting locally made furniture, such as chairs from Turn, hand-woven rugs from Mae Fah Luang, and stools from Bua Phat. &amp;ldquo;This house turned out to be exactly what I was hoping for,&amp;rdquo; says Tantivit. &amp;ldquo;To me, each room has its own character and feeling, so I can pick which room to be in depending on my mood. And with the amount of sunlight and soft breeze that come through the house, none of the rooms have a depressing feeling; instead, they make me feel happy and upbeat. This is a place where I want to be in at the end of a long day at work.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Better still, she says, is the proximity to her family, given that she lives by herself. &amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s good to be able to just walk over to see my family. I still go over there at least once a day to have a meal and hang out with my parents and my 93 year-old grandma. This way I don&amp;rsquo;t ever feel lonely being by myself.&amp;rdquo; For their part, they approve of Tantivit&amp;rsquo;s addition to the family estate. &amp;ldquo;My dad was skeptical about my house at first for it being so modern in his eyes, but he really liked how it turned out.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Sutthida Manopnoi', '2012-02-28', '16:42:01', '2012-02-24', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '11:47', '201202241147', '26_small__155924_vino_cms_.jpg', '26_medium__155924_vino_cms_.jpg', '26_big__155924_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 16, 1, 0, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-2-5-2012-02-27/', 'modern-family.html', '', '', 26, '');
