(27, 25, '2', '5', 'Fun House', '', '', '', 'A self-taught pupil of the Modernist and Brutalist masters, musician Ely Buendia mturned his creative talents to designing his own, eclectic home.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;span style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Photos by &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Miguel Nacianceno&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Project: &lt;strong&gt;Buendia Residence&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Architect: &lt;strong&gt;Mia Guerrero&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;and&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Bradley Reyes&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Location: &lt;strong&gt;Manila, Philippines&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;A self-taught pupil of the Modernist and Brutalist masters, musician Ely Buendia mturned his creative talents to designing his own, eclectic home.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/27/fun_house_1.jpg_140842_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;Nothing matches concrete in strength and elegance,&amp;rdquo; says Ely Buendia. The Filipino rock musician has always had a passion for Modernist and Brutalist architecture, and when it came to building his own home, he looked immediately to the austere material for inspiration.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Influenced by Le Corbusier, Tadao Ando and midcentury architect John Lautner, Buendia started dreaming up his home, making rough, conceptual exterior sketches in a small notebook. &amp;ldquo;People think modern houses all look the same&amp;mdash;when I was doing my sketches, I just wanted something simple,&amp;rdquo; he says. What started out as a straightforward box evolved into a sculptural fa&amp;ccedil;ade that completely defies straight edges and 90-degree angles. The four-storey structure combines sharp angles with surprising bends, plus a series of ground level piloti supporting a heavier structure up top (much like pre-colonial Filipino architecture&amp;rsquo;s nipa hut).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/27/fun_house_2.jpg_140857_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The rough concrete exterior &amp;nbsp;is complemented by classic, mid-century modern furniture and quirky, contemporary artwork.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;I think I designed my house in reverse,&amp;rdquo; he laughs, commenting on the fact that he started out with a shell and worked his way in. After having decided on the basic shape of the structure, Buendia got in touch with architects Mia Guerrero and Bradley Reyes to help execute his interior plans. &amp;ldquo;I downloaded Google Sketchup and started playing around with it for a year. I started with all windows and glass doors but over time, became more realistic and took those elements out for security reasons.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The end result, a combination of Buendia&amp;rsquo;s intuitive sketches and his architects&amp;rsquo; recommendations, is a well-proportioned space that highlights the nakedness of concrete and plays it up with splashes of colour and carefully curated mid-century furniture. One exterior wall extends outwards at an exaggerated angle, allowing for windows that let light in without casting a heavy glare across the living and dining space. The dramatic living room windows are offset by the slim, horizontal window that slices through Buendia&amp;rsquo;s office space and gives the exterior another stroke of Modernism. &amp;ldquo;I think Ely appreciates the nakedness of concrete,&amp;rdquo; remarks architect Mia Guerrero. &amp;ldquo;Instead of covering it up, he leaves everything exposed. There&amp;rsquo;s nothing hidden in this house &amp;ndash; no wall finishes, no decorations, no flooring. If there&amp;rsquo;s an electrical conduit somewhere, everyone can see it.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/27/fun_house_3.jpg_140910_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;That&amp;rsquo;s the one thing I really love about Modernism. You can save money by skipping out on paint, decoration and flooring and your space will still look good,&amp;rdquo; Buendia half-jokes. &amp;ldquo;That&amp;rsquo;s something you can hardly say about anything else.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The second floor&amp;lsquo;s open plan is made flexible by way of several movable dividers &amp;ndash; one in light, polycarbonate material to close off Buendia&amp;rsquo;s office, and another panel swathed in fire engine red, giving the dining area an unexpected pop of colour. The adjacent kitchen is clean, stark and simple, with a fun wall covered in blackboard paint and chalk scribbles.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The kids&amp;rsquo; rooms are also housed on the second level. Fine Arts undergrad student Una has a &amp;ldquo;blank canvas&amp;rdquo; room decked in white that she covered with her own artwork, hand prints and twinkle lights. Eleven-year-old Eon&amp;rsquo;s room on the other hand is inspired by the Beatles&amp;rsquo; Yellow Submarine album. Covered in bright yellows and deep blues, it is a virtual fun house with a bunk for friends sleeping over, a curtained-off nook for his bed, and every inch of space devoted to storage &amp;ndash; from open wall shelving to under-the-table cabinets and a fun, hidden cubby covered by an aluminum roll-up door.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/27/fun_house_4.jpg_140925_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The third floor houses the master bedroom &amp;ndash; not a traditional room in that it has no doors; every part of the space flows seamlessly into the other. The red bedroom looks straight out into the roof deck, its sandbox and the green roof that surrounds it. &amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m a fan of sustainability and &amp;lsquo;smart&amp;rsquo; homes,&amp;rdquo; Buendia says. &amp;ldquo;I like the idea that you can introduce design elements that prevent your home from getting too hot during our ungodly summers. The grass requires practically no maintenance &amp;ndash; I think as long as these green roofs are laid out properly, they work.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;I was quite stubborn about having a flat roof,&amp;rdquo; he says, explaining that the only challenge he&amp;rsquo;s had to face with the house so far was keeping waterproofing in tow &amp;ndash; a common difficulty among flat-roofed structures in countries where rainfall comes many months a year. The originally grayish-green structure is now painted crisp white, owing mostly to the fact that the roof deck needed waterproofing. &amp;ldquo;I decided to paint the whole thing white just to give it a new look &amp;ndash; the kids didn&amp;rsquo;t like the old colour because it was too dark.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;Now, it looks very Villa Savoye from the outside,&amp;rdquo; says architect Guerrero, who says Buendia&amp;rsquo;s fondness for certain movements in architecture informed the design process. &amp;ldquo;At the same time, this house doesn&amp;rsquo;t take itself too seriously &amp;ndash; it&amp;rsquo;s just fun. When he asked for an extension closet, for example, I said, &amp;lsquo;Let&amp;rsquo;s just blend it with everything and make it very basic.&amp;rsquo; Ely told me, &amp;lsquo;No, be creative.&amp;rsquo;&amp;rdquo; The result is an interesting acrylic annex built right onto the roof deck, giving it an amusing, futuristiclooking twist.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/27/fun_house_5.jpg_140940_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;A favourite spot for Buendia and his guests is the roof deck, which has a perimeter surrounded by a simple garden. A main feature of the structure, the deck allows the outdoor to flow directly into the master bedroom and also allows for easy access to the fourth floor recording studio.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Additions were part and parcel of the construction, with the fourth floor recording studio coming into play as the house was being built. &amp;ldquo;I can make music anywhere in the house now and make it as loud as I want,&amp;rdquo; Buendia says. The compact space houses a control room and the actual studio, enveloped in playful yellows and blues, mimicking the bright palette of the bedroom and living area. &amp;ldquo;The house keeps evolving,&amp;rdquo; he admits. &amp;ldquo;When I bought the plot of land, I had another architect draw a house for me but it wasn&amp;rsquo;t what I wanted. Then I played around with Google Sketchup &amp;ndash; it originally had three floors, then I added an extra floor during construction. It&amp;rsquo;s a small lot, only about 210sqm, and the whole process of designing and building was an exercise on the creative use of space.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The interplay between creativity, imagination, and good design gives the house an inimitable air of fun. &amp;ldquo;A concept like this can really just come from someone like Ely &amp;ndash; someone who&amp;rsquo;s just bonkers, really,&amp;rdquo; Guerrero says. &amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s pretty much all original ideas versus something that was just copied off another house or building. Everyone has their own approach to design and this house started out with a vision Ely had from the get go.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The house&amp;rsquo;s evolution doesn&amp;rsquo;t stop after its recent paint overhaul as Buendia dreams up even bigger plans for his home. &amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;d like to get a hold of the two empty lots beside mine for the &amp;lsquo;fortress&amp;rsquo; to be complete,&amp;rdquo; he says. &amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;d also love to add a decontamination chamber in here.&amp;rdquo; He pauses. &amp;ldquo;One can dream,&amp;rdquo; he adds. It may be out of the box, but with a creative genius known for pushing boundaries like Ely Buendia, anything is possible&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Chinggay Labrador', '2012-02-28', '16:40:30', '2012-02-24', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '13:50', '201202241350', '27_small__155822_vino_cms_.jpg', '27_medium__155822_vino_cms_.jpg', '27_big__155822_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 56, 1, 1, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-2-5-2012-02-27/', 'fun-house.html', '', '', 27, ''),
(7, 10, '1', '0', 'Baby in Table', '', '', '', 'Every parent knows the truth of the saying, â€˜They grow up so fast.â€™ Oji Masanori took the speed at which very small people become bigger small people to heart when he created the Baby In Table set. For the first couple of years, the table works as an extended baby seat, while the chair acts as a household stool. Once Junior is on his feet, he can use the table as a desk, the stool as a chair, and his old seat converts to a pocket for books or toys. Finally, the clean-lined Japanese beech table can be used in the living room as a side table when itâ€™s been outgrown. Now, thatâ€™s family planning.', '', '&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Oji Masanori&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	For more info:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://o-ji.jp/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;o-ji.jp&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Every parent knows the truth of the saying, &amp;lsquo;They grow up so fast.&amp;rsquo; Oji Masanori took the speed at which very small people become bigger small people to heart when he created the Baby In Table set. For the first couple of years, the table works as an extended baby seat, while the chair acts as a household stool. Once Junior is on his feet, he can use the table as a desk, the stool as a chair, and his old seat converts to a pocket for books or toys. Finally, the clean-lined Japanese beech table can be used in the living room as a side table when it&amp;rsquo;s been outgrown. Now, that&amp;rsquo;s family planning.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-24', '09:44:17', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:01', '201202091001', '7_small__163744_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '7_big__163744_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 30, 1, 0, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-1-2-2012-02-10/', 'baby-in-table.html', '', '', 7, ''),
(8, 12, '1', '2', 'Smile Stool', '', '', '', 'A great example of applying lateral thinking to production problems, the Smile Stool uses scrap wood from local Balinese furniture makers and embedded rod construction to get around the lack of bentwood production technology available in Indonesia.', '', '&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Studio Hindia&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	For more info:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://studiohindia.blogspot.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;studiohindia.blogspot.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	A great example of applying lateral thinking to production problems, the Smile Stool uses scrap wood from local Balinese furniture makers and embedded rod construction to get around the lack of bentwood production technology available in Indonesia. A piece that&amp;rsquo;s both smart and sustainable, the stool&amp;rsquo;s &amp;lsquo;smile&amp;rsquo; might look cheery, but it is actually an ironic comment on the fact that the Indonesian furniture industry is in decline, and in need of forward-thinking solutions like this one to keep pace withmodern industrial competition.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-24', '09:44:12', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:06', '201202091006', '8_small__163506_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '8_big__163506_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 38, 1, 1, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-1-2-2012-02-10/', 'smile-stool.html', '', '', 8, ''),
(9, 10, '1', '0', 'Origami Island', '', '', '', 'Moving away from his signature â€˜blobâ€™ aesthetic, the prolific Rashid has produced an angular Dupont Corian kitchen inspired by the Japanese art of paper-folding.', '', '&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Karim Rashid for Amr Helmy&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	For more info:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://amrhelmydesigns.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;amrhelmydesigns.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Moving away from his signature &amp;lsquo;blob&amp;rsquo; aesthetic, the prolific Rashid has produced an angular Dupont Corian kitchen inspired by the Japanese art of paper-folding.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-24', '09:44:33', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:06', '201202091006', '9_small__094130_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '9_big__094130_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 21, 1, 0, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-1-2-2012-02-24/', 'origami-island.html', '', '', 9, ''),
(20, 10, '1', '0', 'The Tea Party', '', '', '', 'Bring out the crackers! If you need a reason to treat yourself to a cup of tea, here are seven of the best.', '', '&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Story by Adele Chan&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Photos by Lumina Studio&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;Bring out the crackers! If you need a reason to treat yourself to a cup of tea, here are seven of the best.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Throughout Asia, the ritual of serving tea is regarded as an art. We think it starts with the teapot. These options all have their own charms, yet perform the same duty &amp;ndash; they brew tea and keep it warm until it is ready to be served &amp;ndash; all while looking good. So as you decide which suits your fancy and matches the d&amp;eacute;cor, the real question is: green tea or black?&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;MICHAEL GRAVES TEAPOT&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Alessi&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 320&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Pros: Echoing the style of the designer&amp;rsquo;s bestselling kettle for Alessi, your choice of this teapot asserts your award-winning taste.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Ergonomics plays a key role in its construction &amp;ndash; the wide, triangular spout provides fast flow; the broad base with rounded feet offers stability; and the heatproof PA handle gives excellent grip.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Cons: Its resemblance to the kettle version will confuse many into thinking this pot can be placed on the stove, but like all other teapots here, this is only for serving. So unless you&amp;rsquo;re a Michael Graves enthusiast, you may be better off paying a bit more and buying the kettle, which can actually boil water.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;PUMPKIN TEAPOT&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Royal Selangor&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 370&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Pros: This mini teapot is the perfect size for a single cuppa. Clever holes at the base of the spout act as a decent tea-leaf strainer. All you need is a handful of leaves, a pot of hot water for topping up, and there it is! A fresh cup every time.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Cons: At 11cm high, this teapot is tiny. It really is only good for a single cup of tea, making it the selfish choice of the lot. And at this price, surely you expect a bit more function and practicality. Here&amp;rsquo;s a tip: it makes a pretty pewter paperweight.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;HAKUJI TRADITIONAL TEAPOT&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Muji&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 23&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Pros: Like all things from Muji, the Hakuji teapot has a well thought-out design: the convenient size is good for two cups of tea; the base of the spout is moulded into a miniature colander that strains even the smallest tea leaves; and it is dishwasher and microwave safe. And you can&amp;rsquo;t argue with the price.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Cons: Because the strainer&amp;rsquo;s holes are so small, tea-leaves do get stuck between them, making the teapot a pain to clean.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Furthermore, the traditional Japanese-style handle makes pouring tea a bit trickier and its unusual shape means the teapot requires more shelf space when storing.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;VERSEUSE TEAPOT&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Herm&amp;egrave;s&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 1,500&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Pros: If you like to show off, meet the perfect teapot to do so with. Decorated in the style of Persian miniatures, this fine china is designed for serving tea in style, what with the slender spout and handle lending an elegant silhouette and an accurate pour.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Cons: Tea-time may become a stressful affair, considering the high price of this item. Having said that, if you can actually afford to splash out on this teapot, you can probably afford to break it and replace it with a new one.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;GAYANE TEAPOT&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Kenzo at Proof Living Porcelain&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 585&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Pros: The Gayane teapot traps heat well, with its deep chamber and thickset walls. The perfectly angled spout also stops drips, and grasping the top handles while pouring helps prevent the lid from dropping midway.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	However, the real highlight has to be the tasteful dip-dye gloss finish.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Cons: The cast iron handles may complete this teapot&amp;rsquo;s look, but on a functional note, they make pouring tea harder because they are thin and keep dropping to the sides. Also, like the Herm&amp;egrave;s teapot, there is no internal strainer or basket for sieving out the leaves.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;APPLE RED TEAPOT&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: H&amp;ouml;gan&amp;auml;s Keramik at Style:Nordic&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 249&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Pros: The H&amp;ouml;gan&amp;auml;s serves tea for many while keeping the brew warm with solid walls that act like an oven. A large basket strainer is also included, and fits snugly below the lid.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Plus, it comes with a wooden saucer that is not just practical, but matches the overall design well.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Cons: Making one or two cups of tea suddenly becomes a chore with this bulky pot. Water needs to cover the suspended basket, which results in brewing an entire pot.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Another consideration is that even before adding water to this teapot, it is quite heavy.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;b&gt;HELENA TEAPOT WITH COASTER&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Georg Jensen&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Price: SG$ 320&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Pros: This looks like it belongs in an art museum. The smooth curves and sleek combination of mirror-polished stainless steel and white porcelain make it a surefire conversation piece. What can we say? Like the designer it is named after, the Helena is pure elegance.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	The coaster is included.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Cons: The flat handle is not as comfortable to hold as a rounded one, especially when the teapot is full and quite heavy; and as it extends over the top, it does get in the way when lifting or putting back the lid.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	The porcelain base also feels fragile.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Adele Chan', '2012-02-24', '09:43:55', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '15:15', '201202091515', '20_small__160654_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '20_big__160654_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 52, 1, 0, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-1-1-2012-02-09/', 'the-tea-party.html', '', '', 16, ''),
(22, 410, '4', '10', 'Back to Basics', '', 'A team of young designers is turning one of Indonesiaâ€™s most traditional materials â€“ wood â€“ into modern furniture pieces that â€˜speakâ€™ to their owners.', '', 'A team of young designers is turning one of Indonesiaâ€™s most traditional materials â€“ wood â€“ into modern furniture pieces that â€˜speakâ€™ to their owners.', '', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	TrystLiving CEO Zacky Badrudin, in front of a stack of Betty Chairs in Mesh&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Photos by&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Dittoadita&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;A team of young designers is turning one of Indonesia&amp;rsquo;s most traditional materials &amp;ndash; wood &amp;ndash; into modern furniture pieces that &amp;lsquo;speak&amp;rsquo; to their owners.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;5&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/22/the_bonchu_table_made_of_rare_tea_wood_supported_by_sculpted_stainless_steel_legs_112505_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;The Bonchu Table, made of rare teak wood supported by sculpted stainless steel legs&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Zacky Badrudin, CEO of Jakarta furniture firm TrystLiving, correlates good design with simplicity. Working with teak, mahogany and sonokeling rosewood &amp;ndash; locally-grown timbers in Indonesia &amp;ndash; the company is a master of sleek and streamlined home furnishings that are studies in modern minimalism. A perfect example is their Spise Chair, an archetypal teak chair that is instantly attractive for its straightforwardness and warmth. And though much of minimalism owes its mettle to restraint &amp;ndash; the ability to exert control over a design so it is neither less nor more than it needs to be &amp;ndash; Badrudin maintains that theirs comes via the act of listening. &amp;ldquo;Simply, a good design is created when you listen, then execute,&amp;rdquo; he says, explaining that by &amp;lsquo;listening&amp;rsquo; to the material and letting it &amp;lsquo;speak&amp;rsquo;, their designers are able to work with the colour, texture, shape, and other characteristics of wood, to form polished, practical and pleasing pieces of design.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Why do TrystLiving prefer to work mainly with teak, mahogany, and sonokeling rosewood?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Teak, mahogany and sonokeling rosewood are well-known local timbers that we use because we wanted to make products that say &amp;lsquo;Indonesia&amp;rsquo; by themselves, although with non-traditional design. Every wood or timber is unique. It has its own characteristics, from the feel of its surface to the texture of each timber, and they make a great combination for products.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;5&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;em&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/22/stainless_steel_legs_cut_through_the_body_of_the_blues_cabinet_112337_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Stainless steel legs cut through the body of the Blues Cabinet&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Can you elaborate on what you call&amp;nbsp; the &amp;ldquo;wood experience&amp;rdquo;?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;lsquo;Wood experience&amp;rsquo; is a tag for TrystLiving that we created as a message to our clients that our furniture is not only furniture, but pieces of art made from wooden material. Experiencing the timber surface, looking at the natural texture of different timbers, and seeing [the finished product] as the natural beauty of the earth in modern packaging is our way of conveying our passion in a simple message.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Who are TrystLiving&amp;rsquo;s clients?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	TrystLiving&amp;rsquo;s clients are people who like simplicity for their home. Demographically, many of the younger generation like our style, since people in the TrystLiving team are also young. The company also attracts many older clients who want something different for their home. We also provide product customisations, so clients can get more involved in the design of their homes. We just need to listen to what they need and have some idea of who they are before we start on the design. We have corporations for clients as well. Mostly, they are in the creative industry.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;How do you approach sustainability in your design?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	We get all the timber only from certified vendors in Central and East Java. We are trying to make sustainable products by using only certified timber.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;10&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/22/subtle_detailing_elevates_the_spise_chair_to_a_modern_classic_112649_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Subtle detailing elevates the Spise Chair&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What are your inspirations?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	TrystLiving is inspired by the people around it and inspired by the love of local creativity. If you dig in deep to local culture, you&amp;rsquo;ll find the most amazing creativity within its people and its resources. TrystLiving is representing Indonesia in a modern storytelling of some sort. However, it is hard to single out an inspiration for designing a product, because we pull from many inspirations in designing our furniture. For example, one of our tables is inspired from the texture of the teak wood and we carve it to its detail, while a lounge chair takes inspiration from a boiled egg. So, we gather design inspiration from the smallest things that are near us, to some things that we never imagined getting inspired by.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What is your ultimate goal?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	To produce a furniture design that will last more than 100 years. This is a difficult task. However, with such optimism and unlimited creativity from our team, I can&amp;rsquo;t see why not.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;How has the shop evolved?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Most people who come to our shop to buy a piece of furniture now end up giving us a project. We are planning to expand to produce more home products, and the gallery is expanding nationally. Hopefully, we&amp;rsquo;ll go international within a few years. Creativity is unlimited, and we&amp;rsquo;ll see to it that TrystLiving has more to offer in the near future&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Go Find It!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;TrystLiving&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	Jl. Kemang Utara No. 17A&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	Jakarta Selatan, Indonesia&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	+62 21 719 3315&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	+62 21 719 3312&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;a href=&quot;mailto:info@trystliving.com&quot;&gt;info@trystliving.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Specialty&lt;/strong&gt; : Furniture made from teak, mahogany and sonokeling rosewood from Indonesia&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Top Sellers&lt;/strong&gt; : the Classic Cabinet&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Best Deals&lt;/strong&gt; : Spise Chair made from teak wood&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Coolest Find&lt;/strong&gt; : The Lavoro Table, which is an vintage-meets-modern study desk in teak wood &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Liz Anne Bautista', '2012-02-28', '09:45:42', '2012-02-22', '2012-02-22', '10:45', '10:45', '201202221045', '22_small__094542_vino_cms_.jpg', '22_medium__094542_vino_cms_.jpg', '22_big__094542_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 47, 1, 0, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-4-10-2012-02-28/', 'back-to-basics.html', '', '', 22, ''),
(23, 410, '4', '10', 'Altogether Wonderful', '', '', '', 'An unlikely family â€“ traditional Okinawan ceramics, Modernist Nordic furniture, folk art and avant-garde clothes â€“ make for a surprisingly coherent design store in Japan.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	Keiko Kitamura, co-buyer for Fennica, measuring out a patterned African fabric.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;An unlikely family &amp;ndash; traditional Okinawan ceramics, Modernist Nordic furniture, folk art and avant-garde clothes &amp;ndash; make for a surprisingly coherent design store in Japan.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	A store within a store &amp;ndash; and a brand within a brand &amp;ndash; Fennica is a crafts and clothes store BEAMS. Following the model of its host, &amp;nbsp;Fennica carries a selection of brands and also produces original items. Terry Ellis and Keiko Kitamura, Fennica&amp;rsquo;s London-based buying team, have curated an unexpected farrago of Japanese crafts, richly patterned rugs, Nordic furniture and simple, avant garde clothing. What might at first seem incongruous, on closer inspection becomes a vibrant and cohesive rejection of blank austerity impersonating simplicity. Ellis and Kitamura began clarifying that philosophy over 30 years ago, when they started collecting Modernist objects together in the 80&amp;rsquo;s. Today Fennica, with stores in Tokyo and Kobe, Is a valuable collection of traditional and modern objects with one eye on history and the other on everyday use.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/23/regional_japanese_creamics_155854_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;Regional Japanese ceramics (plates, cups, and bowls) rest on top of table bay Bruno Mathsson, surrounded by Ilmari Tapiovaara chairs&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What is your relationship to the BEAMS and Fennica label?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	We think of ourselves as team-builders.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;The objects and brands Fennica customers can expect to see are&amp;hellip;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Okinawa pottery and glass, Finnish textiles, Tendo Moko furniture and effortlessly stylish clothing.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Describe your ideal Fennica customer.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Effortlessly stylish.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s been said your work emphasises simplicity and modest natural materials. Would you change that description of the Fennica aesthetic?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Maybe we would now subtract the word &amp;ldquo;modest&amp;rdquo; from that description&amp;hellip; in part as a reflection of our refusal to accept to accept that the current mood of austerity &amp;ndash; caused by recent economic crises and series of natural disaster &amp;ndash; should result in bland and uninspiring products becoming the new normal.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/23/three_simple_eamples_of_fennica_160126_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;Three simple examples of Fennica&amp;#39;s hallmark: traditional Okinawan pottery&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Why are Japanese crafts and craftsmen relevan to Fennica?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	It became obvious after a little research that Japanese crafts were an important part of the story of Modernism. The problem was that crafts were seen as unfashionable. We worked with local craftsmen and showed these products in the same space as design objects; Fennica customers quickly understood the mix.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;5&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/23/a_wooden_wunderkammer_160100_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;A wooden wunderkammer of Japanese and European ephemera beside a Bruno Mathsson chair and stool&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Do the same motivations that first drew to collecting craft and Modernist design still draw you today?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	More or less, though it&amp;rsquo;s fair to say that the desire to collect and sell craft objects is a little stronger now than the desire to promote functional design. We want to create stores that extend to reach of the functional object past the purely useful and into areas of life that connect to meaning, emotion, and notions of tradition and heritage.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;At the moment, what is your favourite item in store?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The Fennica Rocker, a beautiful Windsor rocking chair made for Fennica by Matsumoto Mingei Kagu.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;How does the baggage of traditional craft and design (i.e. strong academic/artistic theories and debates) mix with the clothing in Fennica?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The clothing has its own set of baggage, and Fennica customers actually relish the small shocks and clashes that occur when avant-garde fashion philosophies bump up against academic craft/design theory.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Go Find It!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Fennica Shinjuku&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	(inside BEAMS Japan)&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	6/F, 3-32-6 Shinjuku&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Shinjuku-ku, Tokyo, Japan&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	+81 3 5 368 7300&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;a href=&quot;http://blog.beams.co.jp/fennica/&quot; target=&quot;_self&quot;&gt;blog.beams.co.jp/fennica/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Specialty:&lt;/strong&gt; Japanese Crafts, Modernist European furniture&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Top Sellers:&lt;/strong&gt; Okinawan ceramics and Fennica original khakis&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Best Deals:&lt;/strong&gt; Original Fennica collaborations, such as their rocking Chair and Japanese towel&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Coolest Find: &lt;/strong&gt;Silk/cotton handkerchiefs designed by Swaraj Mainee, an Indian textile designer.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Cameron Allan McKean', '2012-02-28', '09:40:48', '2012-02-22', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '15:29', '201202221529', '23_small__094048_vino_cms_.jpg', '23_medium__094048_vino_cms_.jpg', '23_big__094048_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 42, 1, 0, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-4-10-2012-02-28/', 'altogether-wonderful.html', '', '', 23, '');
INSERT INTO `berita` (`id`, `idupline`, `idkategori`, `idkategorisub`, `judul`, `judulinggris`, `subjudul`, `subjudulinggris`, `preview`, `previewinggris`, `deskripsi`, `deskripsiinggris`, `penulis`, `tglpost`, `jampost`, `tgltampil`, `tglselesai`, `jamselesai`, `jamtampil`, `timeunix`, `gambarkecil`, `gambarsedang`, `gambarbesar`, `keterangangambar`, `imagelogo`, `dikomentari`, `dilampirkan`, `dilihat`, `statustampil`, `headline`, `idusers`, `idadmin`, `direktorigambar`, `linkjudul`, `keyword`, `tglbaca`, `urutan`, `wordtag`) VALUES
(24, 49, '4', '9', 'Opposites Attract', '', '', '', 'Drawn together despite their differences, Scot-Indian duo Doshi Levien have welded their dissimilarities into a unique design aesthetic thatâ€™s a cultural revolution.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	Photos by &lt;strong&gt;John Ross&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Drawn together despite their differences, Scot-Indian duo Doshi Levien have welded their dissimilarities into a unique design aesthetic that&amp;rsquo;s a cultural revolution.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot; http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/24/doshi_10.jpg_172227_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Indian fabrics make regular apperarances in their work: This dress is from the duo&amp;#39;s My World installation in 2005&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Things have changed since the furniture design firm Doshi Levien first opened its doors over a decade ago. Since its humble beginnings, the London-based design studio has earned a reputation for progressive and modern designs that combine Indian culture with an industrial bent. Established by the Mumbai-born Nipa Doshi and her Scottish husband Jonathan Levien, over the years Doshi Levien&amp;rsquo;s furniture and domestic designs have attracted the attention of major international players including Intel, Swarovski, Nokia and Moroso&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;The biggest difference between now and when we first started is that today we are approached by high-level clients, companies and organisations,&amp;rdquo; Doshi says. &amp;ldquo;Back in 2000, we had to make a lot more effort to find interesting work and we had a few dead ends, but kept going. After 10 years of being a studio, we feel confident in our ability to design pretty much anything.&amp;rdquo; Doshi Levien&amp;rsquo;s creations embody the &amp;ldquo;unity of opposites.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;4&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/24/doshi_3.jpg_171839_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Since becoming established, Doshi Lavien have worked for a wide range of brands. Their Kali Bathromm collection was ditributed by Authentics&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Their combination of traditional Indian craft and the symbolic with industrial technology and modern manufacturing techniques when Jonathan sees my sketches, he is able to bring them to life. I love that.&amp;rdquo; Levien says that this interlocking approach between the duo&amp;rsquo;s respective skills and ways of perceiving the world results in what he perceives as a new language that neither one of the duo could ever produce on their own.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The pair met as students at the Royal College of Art in London in the 1990s, where they recall being critical of each other&amp;rsquo;s work. Today, they still approach design in different ways, but the dialogue they have developed over the years is vital to their collaboration. &amp;ldquo;We love each other&amp;rsquo;s way of working and have complementary skills. We had, and still have, a lot of mutual respect for one another and we really push each other. In the end, we both had enough of working for other designers, so with a few projects commissioned by Tom Dixon, we decided to quit our jobs and set up Doshi Levien,&amp;rdquo; Doshi says.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/24/doshi_4.jpg_171852_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The launch of Charpoy for Moroso at the Salone del Mobile in Milan puts Doshi Lavien on the international design map&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Over the years the duo&amp;rsquo;s designs have been many and varied, however Doshi says it was the launch of Charpoy for Moroso at the Salone del Mobile in Milan in 2007 that put Doshi Levien on the international design map. Charpoy is a range of four daybeds that combines the detailed handwork has resulted in an innovative range of designs that cross boundaries and disciplines. &amp;ldquo;We are inspired when opposites get together, when an East London Bangladeshi girl dresses in her traditional salwar kameez and wears trainers, speaking a mix of Bengali and Cockney,&amp;rdquo; Levien says. &amp;ldquo;All of this inspires us and challenges our perception of what is ethnic, what is traditional and what is pure.&amp;rdquo; More to the point, it is Doshi&amp;rsquo;s visual direction through collages, painting and drawing combined with Levien&amp;rsquo;s precision as an industrial designer that has allowed the duo to successfully make their own rules in such a competitive industry. &amp;ldquo;Jonathan and I are so different in many ways, and yet there is a willingness and desire to be part of the other person&amp;rsquo;s world and work,&amp;rdquo; Doshi says. &amp;ldquo;I tend to resolve ideas in two dimensions, so of Indian artisans and modern Italian industrial production. Made using cotton and silk mattresses embroidered with boards for the traditional Indian game of Chaupar, the pieces present a new take on the recliner. The lacquered under-frames, CNC machined in Manzano, Italy, stand in stark contrast to the pieces&amp;rsquo; traditional elements. &amp;ldquo;People in attendance were really awestruck to see such fine craftsmanship from India in connection with industrially produced elements,&amp;rdquo; Doshi says. &amp;ldquo;The plurality and multilayering inherent in Charpoy has always been there in our work since the beginning, but it wasn&amp;rsquo;t until 2007 that it became exposed to such a wide audience.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/24/doshi_1.jpg_171610_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n				&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Capo Chair for Cappellini is launched at the Salone del Mobile&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Doshi Levien&amp;rsquo;s latest project Das Haus &amp;ndash; Interiors on Stage is a statement on modern interior culture as an extension of personality. Organised by the annual design event IMM in Cologne, the project focuses on the creation of an artificial living situation within the grounds of the trade fair. To complete their vision, Doshi and Levien will be able to choose from a wide spectrum of products on offer at the fair, from furniture and carpets to wall paint and lighting. At a time when many are cursing globalisation, Doshi Levien&amp;rsquo;s hybrid, approach stands strong, allowing it to combine cultures, industries, technologies and craft techniques. &amp;ldquo;We like to view globalisation as a way to enhance diversity and disrupt homogeneity; as an opportunity to combine the best of both worlds, now that we have access to other countries and cultures like never before,&amp;rdquo; Doshi says.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Anita Surewicz', '2012-02-28', '17:30:40', '2012-02-22', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '17:09', '201202221709', '24_small__092853_vino_cms_.jpg', '24_medium__092853_vino_cms_.jpg', '24_big__092853_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 94, 1, 0, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-4-9-2012-02-28/', 'opposites-attract.html', '', '', 24, ''),
(25, 49, '4', '9', 'Making Light', '', '', '', 'Making Light\r\n\r\nTokujin Yoshioka plays with the ephemeral and the material to create products and spaces that are both uplifting and compelling.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Making Light&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Tokujin Yoshioka plays with the ephemeral and the material to create products and spaces that are both uplifting and compelling.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/25/tokujin_1.jpg_175037_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 1px; margin-bottom: 1px; float: left; width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s easy to be fooled by simplicity. Thanks to decades of advertisements for cleaning products and banking facilities, we&amp;rsquo;ve come to associate the word &amp;lsquo;simple&amp;rsquo; with ideas of ease and speed. From this perspective, Japanese designer Tokujin Yoshioka&amp;rsquo;s work can be disconcertingly easy to misunderstand. His clean-lined, often transparent or colourless works have the kind of appealing clarity &amp;ndash; no pun intended &amp;ndash; that can mislead the viewer into thinking they might have been conceived in a flash of inspiration, rather than by a detailed and penetrating process of thought and development. But Yoshioka&amp;rsquo;s works &amp;ndash; despite their minimalist structural elegance and emotional appeal &amp;ndash; are nothing if not rigorous.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/25/tokujin_2.jpg_175019_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 1px; margin-bottom: 1px; float: right; width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&amp;ldquo;I believe design plays a role in creating new values, and thereby in creating the future. In my designs, I aim to design people&amp;rsquo;s senses towards the future,&amp;rdquo; Yoshioka says. &amp;ldquo;Today, many things, such as sources and means of energy, are going through a major shift.In such an age, I believe design is also shifting from the designing of shapes to the designing of experiences and sensations. I am very curious to know more about how human emotions are triggered and moved, and to integrate these mechanisms.&amp;rdquo; Human engagements with materiality and immateriality have long been hallmarks of Yoshioka&amp;rsquo;s design. After graduating from the Kuwasawa School of Design and apprenticing under the late designer Shiro Kuramata, he first rose to international attention for his work for fashion designer Issey Miyake, designing hats and accessories (though, like Miyake&amp;rsquo;s own work, Yoshioka&amp;rsquo;s silicone hats were closer to art than fashion), and developing&amp;nbsp;interior spaces and exhibitions. For Miyake&amp;rsquo;s A-POC (A Piece of Cloth) store in Aoyama, Yoshioka showed his love of material and ability to create resolved, engaging design solutions by applying the concept behind Miyake&amp;rsquo;s label &amp;ndash; use of a single piece of material to form a garment &amp;ndash; to &amp;lsquo;clothe&amp;rsquo; the store interior, wrapping the interior in moulded aluminium to create a space that is tactile and futuristic.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/25/tokujin_1.jpg_174921_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 1px; margin-bottom: 1px; float: left; width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;Yoshioka&amp;rsquo;s own workspace, created when he set up his studio in 2000, is another reflection of his love of material. Finding an abandoned rice barn in the Shimane Prefecture, Yoshioka had the building shipped piece-by-piece to Daikanyama, in the centre of Tokyo. The building, modernised in the process, still retains the spirit of the original barn. Likewise, Yoshioka&amp;rsquo;s work, despite often using modern materials, retains a certain traditional Japanese spirit of design, drawing on principles of yugen (mystery and subtlety) and mono no aware (a sensitivity to ephemera, and an awareness of transience). &amp;ldquo;In my opinion, Japanese aesthetics is poetic, and Japanese creation is heavily influenced by the elements of nature,&amp;rdquo; Yoshioka says. &amp;ldquo;I try to display the effect of such beauty as nature; the beauty born out of coincidence that can never be reproduced, and the elements of disorderedness that cannot be fully understood by intelligence. Yet, I do not always intend to design or think [in the] Japanese traditional way.&amp;rdquo; Yoshioka&amp;rsquo;s most significant furniture piece &amp;ndash; and his first one to debut at the annual Milan Furniture Fair &amp;ndash; was the Honey-Pop chair. Designed in 2001, each chair is made of 120 layers of honeycombed paper, cut into the shape of an armchair, and starts life flat-packed. To create the chair &amp;ndash; a process in which the user is essential &amp;ndash; the framework is stretched out to form a basic chair shape, and then the user sits in it, fixing the folds of the chair through bodyweight in a way that perfectly conforms to his or her own shape. Visitors to the fair were charmed, as was Italian furniture giant Driade, who commissioned a series of furniture pieces (Tokyo- Pop) based on the essential shape of the chair and rendered in white polypropylene.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/25/tokujin_2.jpg_175053_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 5px; margin-bottom: 5px; float: right; width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;Today, Honey-Pop is part of the permanent collection of New York&amp;rsquo;s Museum of Modern Art, and has been exhibited around the world. &amp;ldquo;I believe that the most beautiful thing in existence is something that can never be reproduced,&amp;rdquo; Yoshioka says. &amp;ldquo;It is the beauty conceived through naturally occurring forces, almost serendipitously. Nature never shows you the exact same thing twice, and that in itself is proof that it is alive.&amp;rdquo; Of all nature&amp;rsquo;s elements, light is Yoshioka&amp;rsquo;s favourite material. &amp;ldquo;The light does not have a definitive form, yet it&amp;nbsp;has the strength to create the mysterious aura that transforms the surrounding atmosphere and to speak most intimately to our deep emotions,&amp;rdquo; he says. &amp;ldquo;Transparent objects are invisible. They are revealed as light hits them, and transforms as light dances. I find the great depth in transparency as it is the representation of light itself.&amp;rdquo; The play of light is a central element in many of Yoshioka&amp;rsquo;s works, including his 2001 Robot Meme exhibition, his 2003 Chair That Disappears in the Rain, his Invisibles collection for Kartell, and his Spectrum exhibition in 2010, which included the mesmerising Rainbow Church installation &amp;ndash; a ninemetre stained-glass &amp;lsquo;window&amp;rsquo; of prisms inspired by the Chapelle du Rosaire in France, which was designed by the French painter Henri Matisse. His dream project, he says, is to bring the Rainbow Church concept to full realisation. &amp;ldquo;I was impressed to see the world of Matisse being expressed by the sunlight of the Provence. Since then, I have been dreaming of designing an architecture where people can feel the light with all senses.&amp;rdquo; The production of an object or installation alone is not the end of Yoshioka&amp;rsquo;s design process, he says. &amp;ldquo;It is not when the shape or the form is fixed that I think the design is finished, yet it is when the design is used or seen by users, or audiences People see things through the filter of their own experiences. Light and air, for example, even though we know and talk a lot about them, there is no substitute for an experience. My design is completed by remembrance of such beauty, which is evoked by our experience and something that is asleep in our mind.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	This year, Yoshioka has already presented one exhibition for the launch of his new Moon Chair for the Moroso Twilight exhibition in Milan, and released the Mi-Ami Chair for Kartell&amp;rsquo;s Kartell Milano exhibition. He&amp;rsquo;s also working on a show with Australia&amp;rsquo;s Sherman Gallery, and directing a special exhibition for watchmaker Cartier, entitled Cartier Time Art. The concept for the exhibition is to &amp;ldquo;merge the spirits of Cartier&amp;rsquo;s craftsmen, a long history, and avant-garde ideas for the future, to highlight Cartier&amp;rsquo;s unique beauty.&amp;rdquo; Having already directed one of Cartier&amp;rsquo;s exhibitions. &amp;lsquo;Story Of...&amp;rsquo; in 2009, Yoshioka will no doubt have an insightful take on the passage of time and its measurement. &amp;ldquo;I am truly inspired when witnessing my design touching people&amp;rsquo;s emotion,&amp;rdquo; he says. &amp;ldquo;Humans are emotional creatures. I want to create a mysterious aura, which could somehow change the entire air around us, such as time, air and light. I would like to spend my life designing things, which will continue to evoke uplifting emotion inside people&amp;rsquo;s soul.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-28', '09:33:05', '2012-02-22', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '17:44', '201202221744', '25_small__093306_vino_cms_.jpg', '25_medium__093306_vino_cms_.jpg', '25_big__093306_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 42, 1, 1, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-4-9-2012-02-28/', 'making-light.html', '', '', 25, ''),
(11, 12, '1', '2', 'Versatile Arc', '', '', '', 'A 3D arrow-head shaped ceramic tile from Turkish firm KÃœtahya Seramik allows users to create a variety of textured patterns.', '', '&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Yigit Ozer for K&amp;Uuml;tahya Seramik&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	For more info:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://kutahyaseramik.com.tr/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;kutahyaseramik.com.tr&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	A 3D arrow-head shaped ceramic tile from Turkish firm K&amp;Uuml;tahya Seramik allows users to create a variety of textured patterns.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-24', '09:44:00', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:07', '201202091007', '11_small__163801_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '11_big__163801_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 32, 1, 0, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-1-2-2012-02-09/', 'versatile-arc.html', '', '', 13, ''),
(12, 10, '1', '0', ' The Narcissist', '', '', '', 'A dressing table set with three mirrors and inlaid with crystals is the very zenith of the â€˜vanity cabinetâ€™ concept.', '', '&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Designed by: Neri &amp;amp; Hu for BD Barcelona Design&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	For more info:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bdbarcelona.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;bdbarcelona.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	A dressing table set with three mirrors and inlaid with crystals is the very zenith of the &amp;lsquo;vanity cabinet&amp;rsquo; concept.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-24', '09:43:23', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:07', '201202091007', '12_small__163728_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '12_big__163728_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 56, 1, 1, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-1-2-2012-02-09/', '-the-narcissist.html', '', '', 20, ''),
(13, 26, '2', '6', 'OUTSIDE THE BOXES', '', '', '', 'An unusual property gives rise to an unusual house in one of Bangaloreâ€™s suburbs.', '', '&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Project: &lt;strong&gt;House of Pavilions&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Location:&lt;strong&gt; Bangalore, India&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Architect: &lt;strong&gt;Architecture Paradigm&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;a href=&quot;http://architectureparadigm.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;architectureparadigm.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;An unusual property gives rise to an unusual house in one of Bangalore&amp;rsquo;s suburbs.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Designed to house three generations of a family, this multi-level home by Architecture Paradigm, sited on a large, treelined property in Bangalore, India, plays with ideas of public and private spaces, and indoors and out. Multiple pavilions are arranged along a central &amp;lsquo;movement spine&amp;rsquo;, with social gathering-places like the kitchen and family rooms closest to the front entrance, and bedrooms hidden at the far end of the house. Upstairs, the son&amp;rsquo;s bedroom is a separate retreat. Numerous terraces offer lots of opportunities for outdoor living, and bodies of water &amp;ndash; which act as thermal regulators &amp;ndash; weave throughout the house. Slatted walls offer semi-private views of the surrounding gardens, and sliding panels allow the public/private aspect of the house to become more dynamic and link together built and unbuilt spaces. We like the sloped roofs, which add to the structure&amp;rsquo;s sense of movement and interplay.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Anita Surewicz', '2012-02-28', '16:59:50', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:08', '201202091008', '13_small__100332_vino_cms_.jpg', '13_medium__100332_vino_cms_.png', '13_big__100332_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 52, 1, 1, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-2-6-2012-02-27/', 'outside-the-boxes.html', '', '', 13, ''),
(14, 26, '2', '6', 'ALL CHANGE', '', '', '', 'A French-born, Japan-based architect rolls out a new idea for keeping a family home fresh through the years.', '', '&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Project: &lt;strong&gt;Nozawa Apartment&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Location: &lt;strong&gt;Tokyo, Japan&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Architect: &lt;strong&gt;Emmanuelle Moureaux&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;a href=&quot;http://emmanuelle.jp/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;emmanuelle.jp&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;A French-born, Japan-based architect rolls out a new idea for keeping a family home fresh through the years.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The Tokyo-based French architect Emmanuelle Moureaux is known for her use of layering and colour to create charming and inventive buildings. Her Nozawa apartment defies conventional notions of buildings as static, by incorporating movable shikiri shelves to simultaneously enable different space creation possibilities and to provide an abundant amount of storage. The double-sided cabinet partitions can be moved freely and are decorated in a range of vibrant colours. Not confined to room units, the apartment&amp;rsquo;s interior &amp;ndash; which at the moment consists of a children&amp;rsquo;s space, a work space and a living room &amp;ndash; can be reinvented to suit a growing family or the changing moods of its inhabitants.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', '', 'Anita Surewicz', '2012-02-28', '16:51:41', '2012-02-09', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:18', '201202091018', '14_small__095951_vino_cms_.jpg', '14_medium__095951_vino_cms_.png', '14_big__095951_vino_cms_.jpg', 'All Change', '', 0, 0, 70, 1, 1, 2, 2, 'filemodul/news/file_item-2-6-2012-02-27/', 'all-change.html', '', '', 14, ''),
(42, 23, '2', '3', 'Paradise Found', '', '', '', 'By translating the tropical resort style to a domestic setting, every day feels like a vacation at the Heneberry family home.', '', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;\r\n	Photos by Justin &lt;strong&gt;Ngiam and Michael Yeoh&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;By translating the tropical resort style to a domestic setting, every day feels like a vacation at the Heneberry family home.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/42/paradise_found_1.jpg_090637_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Heneberry&amp;rsquo;s experiments with various finishes can be seen throughout the house like the Tadalekt finishing used on the counter/shelf in the study&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Irish expatriate Tony Heneberry and his Australian partner Margaret Wing spent the better part of their 20 years in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, living in apartments. Now, with their two children, Jack, 10, and Sophie, 6, they&amp;rsquo;ve settled into their dream house &amp;ndash; an extensively renovated 1960s bungalow at the edge of a forest reserve just minutes outside the city. Looking at the expansive spaces of the house, it&amp;rsquo;s hard to believe its original owner had sub-divided it into a rabbit-warren of rooms, but Heneberry&amp;rsquo;s steely resolve and inspired approach to embracing the environment has reshaped itinto an eloquent ode to tropical living.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/42/paradise_found_3.jpg_090813_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 8px; margin-top: 2px; margin-bottom: 2px; float: right; width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;Tony &amp;nbsp; Heneberry:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;Margaret and I have been looking for years and took a long time to find this place; we liked this area because to have a jungle aspect so close to the city is very special. I&amp;rsquo;ve had an office round the corner for about 14 years, so when we heard that this house was going on the market, it was an instant decision. From the front it looks very nondescript but then you go to the back and you realise, &amp;lsquo;Wow!&amp;rsquo; We saw the potential here instantly, although we had to make it come alive.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;5&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/42/paradise_found_2.jpg_090802_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;From the breakfast counter, Heneberry and Wing have a bird&amp;rsquo;s eye view of the entire living space, all the way to the end of the deck, because the whole space has been modified into one level. This makes it easy to keep an eye on the kids, whether they are in the house or the pool.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	What you see today, are the fruits of my collaboration with my JTJ Design partners Jo England and Jessica Lim &amp;ndash; we&amp;rsquo;ve been friends for a long time and our children are all about the same age. Although we all come from different fields (I&amp;rsquo;m a marine engineer but run a PR, advertising and investment company, Jo is a graphic designer and Jess is an accountant turned realtor), having discussed working on properties so much we finally formed JTJ Design. In the business, Jo and I deal with the design aspects, with Jo specialising in interior design and I, the construction while Jess does the real estate bit. The advantage is that we are not a service per se &amp;ndash; we buy our own properties then become our own clients &amp;ndash; so we don&amp;rsquo;t have to compromise and then we take it to the market. It allows us to be a bit more progressive, like in this house (which initially was destined for resale) where we resisted installing any air conditioning and the windows are always open. We also have the luxury of experimenting, as we have full-time artisans who perfect finishings that are then used in our other projects.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	This house was still in its original shape and form when we bought it, but as the previous owner&amp;rsquo;s family grew, it got divided into smaller areas. We cleared everything out and unified all the living spaces, which were on various levels into one smooth clean expanse. Now the kitchen flows to the living room to the deck and then the pool beyond. We all knew conceptually that the jungle would be the feature of everything, but in terms of specific layout, having everything on one plane works very well for us as a family. Particularly when you have very young kids &amp;ndash; you can stand in the kitchen or in the living room and have a clear line of sight of them playing.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;5&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/42/paradise_found_4.jpg_090857_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Jack and Sophie make full use of the family oriented home, which was designed to evolve and continue to cater to their needs as they grow older.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Before you walk into the main door, you walk through a path bordered with a miniature &amp;ldquo;jungle&amp;rdquo;. We incorporated this so that you get the feeling that the jungle never stops and it&amp;rsquo;s the house in the jungle rather than the house by the jungle. The open feel of the landscaping is very loose and raw and we planted trees that you could possibly see when walking in the jungle. Wildlife is encouraged and we get to see all sorts of birds nesting in the trees, squirrels, monkeys, even snakes. Eventually, when all of the trees mature, we&amp;rsquo;d like to have the house just disappear underneath the trees. The benefit of this is that you end up with a cooler buffer zone and the air temperature in this house is five to six degrees cooler than the general temperature.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Another big transformation is the lower ground floor family space. It was originally a carpark that had been converted to a storage area. We created a doorway so you could access it directly from the house, and were careful not to divide it up into little cubicles. What we did instead was to divide it into spaces &amp;ndash; one section into a guest room and next to it a bathroom with a glorious outdoor shower, and one large family area. The flooring for the guest room was made from off-cuts from the deck, so we got a hardwood floor that costs us nothing. The cement floor is original; we just brought in a stone polisher and ground it back to give it a glossy feel.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;5&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/42/paradise_found_5.jpg_090909_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Experimenting with finishes is a big part of what JTJ Design does and one of the finishes we used quite extensively in the kitchen, the barbecue pit, the guest room and bathroom is called Tadalekt. Tadalekt is a Moroccan finishing using a soappolishing technique that gives a waterproofing effect and also gives the surface a beautiful glassy finish. We modified it somewhat by leaving out the paint pigment so it&amp;rsquo;s a beautiful pale gray. Another experiment that paid off was the garden wall &amp;ndash; when we demolished the ugly 1960s wall-facing, we discovered interesting textures in the rubble and used the contrasting colours to form a wall with a striped pattern. It was a painstaking process and took six weeks, but I think it&amp;rsquo;s worth it, although some people may find it too unfinished.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Our house is still evolving, there&amp;rsquo;s a triangular area near the deck that has been reserved for a spa. We&amp;rsquo;re going to cover it and extend it from the living space, and put in a family bath so it&amp;rsquo;ll be slightly elevated and you can look out to the pool. Hidden behind it will be a sauna with a glass plane that will look out into the jungle. We also plan to put a turf down the side of the family area so the kids can play football there. I also wanted to add balconies to the bedrooms so that even when you&amp;rsquo;re lying down, you can overlook the landscaping. Truth be told, I don&amp;rsquo;t think this house will ever stop evolving. As long as we are living here, I think we&amp;rsquo;ll always be experimenting &amp;ndash; this is our lab-cum-playground.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'As Told to <b>Choo Ai Ling</b>', '2012-02-28', '15:55:49', '2012-02-27', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '09:00', '201202270900', '42_small__141045_vino_cms_.jpg', '42_medium__141045_vino_cms_.jpg', '42_big__141045_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 36, 1, 0, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-2-3-2012-02-28/', 'paradise-found.html', '', '', 42, '');
