(43, 611, '6', '11', 'An Introduction to Plastics', '', '', '', 'Right now, youâ€™re almost certain to be touching plastic.', '', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Right now, you&amp;rsquo;re almost certain to be touching plastic.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	It might be something obvious, like the polyethylene terephthalate water bottle you&amp;rsquo;re about to take a sip from, your silicone watchstrap, or the melamine resin surface of the desk you&amp;rsquo;re supposed to be working behind. Perhaps it&amp;rsquo;s less obvious, like your polymethyl methacrylate contact lenses, the two percent elastane content that keeps your jeans fitting snugly, or the polyvinyl chloride acetate credit card slipped into the back pocket of those jeans. Whatever it is, ever since the first commercial type of plastic &amp;ndash; Bakelite, that staple of billiard balls and Mah Jongg sets &amp;ndash; was invented in 1907 by Belgian chemist Leo Baekeland, the material has gone from a novelty, to widespread, to nearubiquitous in modern design.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The pervasiveness of plastic was recently noted by author Susan Freinkel when she tried to go a day without touching any. Falling at the first hurdle &amp;ndash; her plastic toilet seat &amp;ndash; she revised her challenge to counting the number of plastic items she did touch in the course of an average day. Over 200 items later, she had the foundation for her book Plastic: A Toxic Love mStory. The book charts the lives of eight common plastic items, and compares the way the development of plastics has advanced civilisation with the looming crises it has potentially created. &amp;ldquo;Plastics freed us from the confines of the natural world, from the material constraints and limited supplies that had long bounded human activity,&amp;rdquo; Freinkel writes. &amp;ldquo;That new elasticity unfixed social boundaries as well. The arrival of these malleable and versatile materials gave producers the ability to create a treasure trovem of new products while expanding opportunities for people of modest means to become consumers.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	So what is plastic, exactly? Simply put, it&amp;rsquo;s a synthetic or semi-synthetic solid that can be shaped into various forms. Technically, it&amp;rsquo;s a polymer of one of two types a thermoplastic that can be heated and moulded repeatedly, or a thermoset that retains a particular mould permanently once it is cooled. Perspex &amp;ndash; a plastic often used for transparent furniture and tableware &amp;ndash; is a thermoplastic, and the trusty aforementioned Bakelite is a thermoset. From a sustainability point of view, the key difference is that thermoplastics can be recycled, while thermosets cannot. Plastics are generally made from petrochemicals &amp;ndash; crude oil, and natural gas.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Today, Asia is the biggest regional consumer of plastics in the world &amp;ndash; not surprising, given plastic&amp;rsquo;s key role in industrialization and economic development. China leads the world for plastics use &amp;ndash; per capita, consumption has increased by a startling 270 percent (46kg per person) over the last five years, according to the China Plastics Processing Industry Association. And plastic companies recognisethe growth potential in the market &amp;ndash; there are at least two or three major plastics conferences in the region every month, and the recent Chinaplas 2011 trade show attracted almost 100,000 visitors &amp;ndash; a third as many as attend the famed annual Milan Furniture Fair. By 2015, China is expected to be producing 65 percent of the world&amp;rsquo;s polycarbonates &amp;ndash; the plastic used extensively in electronic components, construction and automotive parts, as well as sunglass lenses, digital disks and, controversially, drinking bottles (see BPA under Acronyms You Should Know). Still, with global recycling rates rarely breaking 50 percent even for the most easily recycled plastics under the most encouraging governmental systems (around 28 percent PET recycling in the US and 48 percent in the EU), and the price of plastic rising as a reflection of oil costs, plastic&amp;rsquo;s stronghold as the king of cheap materials is looking a little less secure in the 21st century&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DONE RIGHT&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;A Clear Winner&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Story by &lt;strong&gt;Christopher DeWolf&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Illustrations by &lt;strong&gt;Ross Murray&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Plastic&amp;rsquo;s appeal as a material for modern design is transparently obvious.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Gone are the days when plastic furniture meant a cheap white chair sitting forlornly in the back garden. Some of the world&amp;rsquo;s best designers have embraced high-quality plastic to create remarkably sophisticated tables and chairs that are longer-lasting and more imaginative than was ever possible with furniture made from natural materials.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Leading the way is Philippe Starck, the legendary French designer, whose line of polycarbonate chairs for Italian brand Kartell changed perceptions of plastic furniture mforever. Starck&amp;rsquo;s first plastic chair was the candy-hued La Marie, whose delicate, glasslike appearance belies its inherent strength. But it wasn&amp;rsquo;t until 2002, when Starck came out with the transparent Louis Ghost chair &amp;ndash; a cheeky, beguiling take on the tradition-bound Louis XV armchair &amp;ndash; that highend plastic furniture really captured the world&amp;rsquo;s interest.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Starck&amp;rsquo;s distinct brand of humour is one of his most controversial aspects, and not everyone appreciated the &amp;ldquo;one-liner&amp;rdquo; joke behind the Louis Ghost chair, as it was described by the British design critic Stephen Bayley. (He also complained that it is &amp;ldquo;easily scratched.&amp;rdquo;) Without compromising a high-minded approach, other designers have softened Starck&amp;rsquo;s edge, creating furniture that is both beautiful and practical.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Hong Kong designer Danny Fang is one example. One of his earliest designs is the Matryoshka, a wicker patio set that can be hidden away, like a Russian doll, into a single chair. Instead of rattan, Fang&amp;rsquo;s wicker is made from plastic fibres, which are ideal for outdoor use. His other chairs are similarly sturdy, like the black polycarbonate Gepetto chair, which was inspired by Ming Dynasty furniture carved from a single piece of wood. Unlike 16thcentury wood chairs, though, Gepetto can be stacked &amp;ndash; &amp;ldquo;and if you throw it down a flight of stairs,&amp;rdquo; says Fang, &amp;ldquo;it won&amp;rsquo;t break, it will bounce.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;DONE WRONG&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Cast Away&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Story by &lt;strong&gt;Hanna Scott&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Photos supplied by &lt;strong&gt;Choi Jeong Hwa&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Where does old plastic go to die? Unfortunately, like old sailors, it often goes to sea.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	In the winter of 1992, a container ship travelling from Hong Kong to Washington encountered a fierce storm in the North Pacific. As the ship was tossed about by vicious waves, 12 containers fell overboard, including one containing 28,800 plastic bath toys. Over the next two decades, the toys, including many rubber duckies, were pulled by ocean currents up to the Arctic Ocean and down to the coast of England, where some of them were recovered 15 years later.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Every day, the same thing happens to millions of tonnes of bags, containers and other plastic waste. There is so much plastic floating around in the ocean that a vast section of the eastern Pacific has been transformed into a wasteland where small bits of plastic circulate round and round in an endless loop. In this Plastic Vortex, as it is known, the plastic is up to 24 times more densely-packed than plankton, the small organisms on which fish and other marine animals survive. Similar concentrations of plastic exist in every other ocean except the Arctic.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	It turns out that plastic&amp;rsquo;s durability, the very quality that makes it such a useful material, has also led to environmental disaster. Less than five percent of plastic is recycled, so when you toss that takeaway container into the rubbish bin, it often ends up washed out to sea. Some of its is swept back to shore, where it costs millions of dollars to clean up. But most of it stays at sea, where the cost to wildlife is even greater. The world&amp;rsquo;s oceans are now so infested by plastic that many animals mistake it for food. In the Pacific, albatross feed plastic to their young, who then die of starvation and plastic poisoning, mtheir bellies filled with scraps of candy wrappers and shopping bags.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;GREAT IDEA&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Plastic Fantastic&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Story by &lt;strong&gt;Hanna Scott&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Photos supplied by &lt;strong&gt;Choi Jeong Hwa&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Recycling cheap plastics into dazzlingly energetic environments, Korean artist Choi Jeong Hwa gives mass production items one-off appeal.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The candy colours of modern plastics are all part of the appeal for Korean artist and designer Choi Jeong Hwa, who uses markets as a key source of inspiration and material, fine-tuning mass-produced excess into exuberantly crafted art. With exhibition titles such as Plastic Paradise, the work is high art made from cheap and readily available materials. At their best, Jeong Hwa&amp;rsquo;s artworks sidestep the distinction between art and life, instead sitting right at the point where art becomes life, like his cabletie pendant lamp that glows like a tropical anemone, or his red chandelier made from a tangle of plastic tubing.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	His Pop Art sensibility is equally at home developing architecture, theatre design and interiors as it isoperating within the contemporary art circuit. In November 2010 in Seoul, Jeong Hwa collaborated with leading dance choreographer Ahn Ae Soon to design a dance performance set that used an overload of plastic colanders as both prop and furniture. Collaborating in this way makes great immersive theatre, so it is no accident that many of his exhibitions operate like stage sets. His environments of mirrored vinyl festooned with colourful, glamorous plastic beads are scenes where we can transport ourselves out of the mundane world and into another, more fantastic, empire. Walking into the bathroom remodelled by Jeong Hwa at Ggooll, an alternative project space in Seoul, is like entering a parallel universe. The mirrored walls reflect into infinity and the clusters of plastic jewels hanging from the ceiling are a captivating inconvenience to navigate, turning a normally prosaic pit stop into an adventure.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	His environments use a culture of excess and abundance to create objects and places more fabulous and perhaps bittersweet than the real thing. The life cycle of his projects is always a consideration &amp;ndash; the properties of plastic mean it is permanent and will not decay &amp;ndash; so his works often play on this idea by casting perishable flowers and food, the traditional msymbols of worldly transience, into plastic. By covering real trees with fake plastic flowers, his works defy the seasons mand provide cheery blossoms all year round.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;THE FUTURE&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;The Takeaway&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Story by &lt;strong&gt;Christopher DeWolf&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	Illustrations by &lt;strong&gt;Ross Murray&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Across Asia, governments are realising it&amp;rsquo;s more effective to reduce plastic production than deal with plastic waste.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Every November, thousands of volunteers take to the world&amp;rsquo;s beaches for the two-day International Coastal Cleanup, which aims to raise awareness about waste in the world&amp;rsquo;s oceans. And every year, they walk away with thousands of tonnes of debris, most of it household items like plastic bags, bottles and food containers. In Hong Kong alone, volunteers hauled away 31,113kg of waste, more than half of it plastic.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s getting worse,&amp;rdquo; says Lisa Christensen, founding director of Ecovision Asia, which organizes the Hong Kong cleanup. &amp;ldquo;There&amp;rsquo;s just more and more rubbish every year. People call it marine pollution, but it&amp;rsquo;s really plastic pollution. Plastic is very useful material but it&amp;rsquo;s the &amp;nbsp;single-use plastic items like bottles, forks, lids and cigarette lighters that are doing the most damage.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The problem extends to land, where space for garbage dumps is fast running out. Hong Kong expects to run out of landfill space by the middle of this space. The situation isn&amp;rsquo;t much better in other spacedeprived Asian cities, many of which are already struggling to deal with other costly environmental problems like water and air pollution.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Still, governments across the region seem to have recognized the problem. In 2009, Hong Kong introduced a tax on plastic bags handed out at the city&amp;rsquo;s major retail chains, which has led to a remarkable 90 percent drop in the number of bags handed out at those shops. In China, an outright ban on super-thin plastic bags cut plastic bag use by 66 percent and saved 1.6 million tones of petroleum that would have been used to manufacture those bags.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	There is also hope in new technology. Japan already recycles close to one third of its plastic waste and another 50 percent is burned to generate heat and electric power. But&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	one Japanese inventor, Akinori Ito, has developed a tabletop machine that can covert polyethylene, polystyrene and polypropylene into oil. One kg of plastic makes one litre of oil at a cost of around 20 yen, and in its crude form, it can be used to power stoves and generators.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	There are also ways to reduce plastic consumption. Environmental activists want to see more countries legislate producer take-back laws, which would require them to take back and recycle plastic bottles, similar to how glass bottles can be returned for a refund in many parts of the world. Some are lobbying for an outright ban on polystyrene, which not only takes hundreds of years to degrade, but breaks down into small particles that poison animals and can be particularly hard to clean up.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	In the end, plastic might do itself in, since its production relies fossil fuels that are growing increasingly scarce. But even when oil, gas and coal run out and plastic becomes prohibitively expensive to produce, we will still be cleaning up the mess we&amp;rsquo;ve already made.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-27', '10:49:33', '2012-02-27', '2012-02-27', '10:18', '10:18', '201202271018', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 10, 1, 0, 3, 3, '', 'an-introduction-to-plastics.html', '', '', 43, ''),
(44, 611, '6', '11', 'An Introduction to Renovating', '', '', '', 'Renovating an existing house, apartment or building is a great way to achieve your dream home â€“ or something close to it â€“ more cheaply and quickly than starting from scratch. But it comes with its own set of challenges.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;span style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Photos by &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Iain McKenzie&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Renovating an existing house, apartment or building is a great way to achieve your dream home &amp;ndash; or something close to it &amp;ndash; more cheaply and quickly than starting from scratch. But it comes with its own set of challenges.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	From colonial villas, Federation homes and traditional Beijing hutongs,to Singapore shophouses and Hong Kong apartment blocks, the Asia- Pacific has a vast stock of existing residential buildings that can be updated for the 21st century. We look at three successful residential modernisations of buildings typical to the region.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;The Converted Industrial Building&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/44/an_introduction_to_renovating_1.jpg_105638_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	It&amp;rsquo;s not quite Manhattan&amp;rsquo;s Meatpacking District, but the inner-city suburb of Surry Hills in Sydney has some of the same mixed-use industrial, fashion and revived residential usage as the famously gentrified New York neighbourhood. In this project, led by Brisbane based architect Ian Moore, a tall, slim and deep late-19&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; century warehouse was converted into a two-level, onebedroom home for a couple.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The building had already been through a series of different uses before its residential incarnation &amp;ndash; first as a grocery storehouse, then 35 years as an engineering workshop, before it was converted to an artist&amp;rsquo;s studio and residence in the 1970s.The new owners wanted a sleek, inner city pad that retained references to the building&amp;rsquo;s history. Moore&amp;rsquo;s plan for the property utilises clever motifs &amp;ndash; such as rendering all the retained inner structures in white, while all the new elements were painted black &amp;ndash; to draw a visual line between old and new. This concept was carried through to the black and white rubber flooring, and the black anodised aluminium joinery.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/44/an_introduction_to_renovating_2.jpg_105657_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The open plan of warehouse buildings gives them a&amp;nbsp; deal of flexibility when it comes to renovations, and Moore took full advantage of that, creating a high volume living space on the entrance floor with a fullheight wall of books. The kitchen overlooks the living space from half a level above, shielded by a black steel plate structure. On the upper level are the master suite and study/ lounge, separated by the Corian- lined bathroom in the middle. Light from a new clerestory window at the top of the bathroom pours into the space and illuminates the study and bedroom through clear glazing on either side.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The property runs between two streets, allowing Moore to divide the garage entrance and visitor&amp;nbsp; entrance. The new front door faces onto a quiet closed street, and is adjacent to a heritage- listed sandstone wall. A steel plate runs from ground level to roof level, framing the frosted glass door and tower of windows, playing off against the existing brickwork of the building, where changes in the type and structures of the brickwork reveal former window openings that have since been bricked over. At the other end of the house, the garage door is formed from steel &amp;lsquo;planks&amp;rsquo; that evoke the original timber door, and the address rendered in water-jet-cut steel letters is a nod to the original engineering workshop signage. &amp;ldquo;The contrast between the precision of the steelwork and the patina of the original brickwork summarises the transformation from 19th to 21st centuries and from industrial to residential,&amp;rdquo; says Moore.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Before After&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Japan&amp;rsquo;s preoccupation with new bespoke homes has honed the skills of its architects, but the time has come to refurbish the existing housing stock.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/44/an_introduction_to_renovating___before_after2.jpg_105720_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;In the new millennium, Japan&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is undergoing a cultural shift when it comes to renovating. Although the country has many beautiful centuriesold traditional wood-joinery buildings, for most of the last century, houses were designed to last for one generation only, and were pulled down after only 20 or 30 years.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	But modern pressures of increasing urban density and an aging population mean this approach is becoming less and less manageable. In late 2009, Japan&amp;rsquo;s former Prime Minister Yukio Hatoyama introduced a package of incentives (including rebates for insulation and double-glazing) for homeowners to renovate older houses, rather than tear them down and rebuild, and pledged to reduce spending on construction (a pledge somewhat thrown into chaos by last year&amp;rsquo;s earthquake and tsunami).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/44/an_introduction_to_renovating___before_after.jpg_105710_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	And the idea is catching on: the concept of &amp;lsquo;skeleton infill&amp;rsquo; renovation has started to gain traction in Japan &amp;ndash; maintaining the exterior structure of a building, while changing the insides. Several large Japanese companies have started to offer IKEA-style customizable fit-outs, including Muji, who joined forces with the interior design and renovation firm Rebita to create a range of Muji interior collections, and Atelier OPA, which released a range of modular &amp;lsquo;stations&amp;rsquo; for sleeping, eating and working.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	This project in the northwest Egota region of Toyko by Suppose Design Office, led by architect Makoto Tanijiri, is a great example of the &amp;lsquo;skeleton infill&amp;rsquo; concept. A three-storey steel-frame building that was used as a series of apartments was hollowed out and redesigned to improve the flow and modernise the spaces, creating six new apartments, including a double-storey penthouse for the owner of the building. &amp;ldquo;The common points of the renovation for the all rooms was to remove something, not to add, like in a normal renovation, without changing a big part of the plans,&amp;rdquo; says Tanijiri. &amp;ldquo;We considered carefully how to remove parts of the house, and also what should be kept.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/44/an_introduction_to_renovating___before_after3.jpg_105734_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The floors at the first level were taken out, spaces were widened and the second floor ceilings were largely removed. On the third floor, extra insulation was inserted into the walls, and waterproofing was added to shore up the building, which was starting to show signs of its age. Finally, the rooftop conservatory was transformed into an expansive bathroom, sheltered by creepers and potted plants, but with wide views across the city. A mix of exposed, painted trusses and wooden false ceilings give the interior of the building a look that is both industrial and refined in parts. &amp;ldquo;We were seeking and challenged new ways of renovation that would be getting more demand in the society from now,&amp;rdquo; acknowledges Tanijiri. &amp;ldquo;The renovated house shows different faces of its new characteristics in keeping its memories of the past for the last decades.&amp;rdquo; He says the redesign mixes old and new in a natural way, &amp;ldquo;something like vintage denim pants with a new shirt&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Melinda Williams', '2012-02-27', '11:07:03', '2012-02-27', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '10:50', '201202271050', '44_small__110703_vino_cms_.jpg', '44_medium__110703_vino_cms_.jpg', '44_big__110703_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 34, 1, 0, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-6-11-2012-02-27/', 'an-introduction-to-renovating.html', '', '', 44, ''),
(45, 38, '3', '8', 'Geometric Varietals', '', '', '', 'Studio SKLIM outfits a new wine bistro with a strong concept of chiselled volumes and geometric cutouts.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Studio SKLIM outfits a new wine bistro with a strong concept of chiselled volumes and geometric cutouts.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;center&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 415px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/45/geometric_varietals_1.jpg_111850_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/45/geometric_varietals_2.jpg_111903_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;float: left; width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	With high duties levied on the country&amp;rsquo;s alcohol imports, an afterwork tipple in Singapore never comes cheap. But a new entrant to the F&amp;amp;B scene is creating a paradigm shift with The Tastings Room &amp;ndash; a wine bistro where quality wines and food are accessible to everyone. A reasonable price list, a thoughtful menu with food-wine pairing suggestions, and not least, a stronglyconceptualised bistro setting make it a great place to drop in for a long lunch with colleagues or to loosen that tie on a Friday night.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/45/geometric_varietals_3.jpg_112556_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 173px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The design was helmed by local designer Kevin Lim of Studio SKLIM, who, in respect to the bistro&amp;rsquo;s ideology, refrained from outfitting the space with the metaphorical suit, despite it being located in the CBD. Through most of the bistro space, features and forms slash together &amp;ndash; dynamic enough to evoke a casual vibe, but kept quiet in reference to the refinements of wine appreciation. The geometric fit-out is not purely an aesthetic decision, but a studied result of form &amp;ndash; voluminous or tapered to design parameters and hung floating or grounded according to the practical needs of the bistro&amp;rsquo;s busy programme.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Unfussy, this interior design makes for some interesting food for thought, as Lim reveals in his clever working of sight lines: &amp;ldquo;A selection of strategically placed visibility cut-outs are subtracted from these dark volumes to reveal internal workings of each enclosure as framed spatial appetisers, perhaps how like wine should be, one sip at a time and always in a controlled manner.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', '', '2012-02-28', '14:27:38', '2012-02-27', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '11:16', '201202271116', '45_small__142738_vino_cms_.jpg', '45_medium__142738_vino_cms_.jpg', '45_big__142738_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 10, 1, 0, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-3-8-2012-02-28/', 'geometric-varietals.html', '', '', 45, '');
INSERT INTO `berita` (`id`, `idupline`, `idkategori`, `idkategorisub`, `judul`, `judulinggris`, `subjudul`, `subjudulinggris`, `preview`, `previewinggris`, `deskripsi`, `deskripsiinggris`, `penulis`, `tglpost`, `jampost`, `tgltampil`, `tglselesai`, `jamselesai`, `jamtampil`, `timeunix`, `gambarkecil`, `gambarsedang`, `gambarbesar`, `keterangangambar`, `imagelogo`, `dikomentari`, `dilampirkan`, `dilihat`, `statustampil`, `headline`, `idusers`, `idadmin`, `direktorigambar`, `linkjudul`, `keyword`, `tglbaca`, `urutan`, `wordtag`) VALUES
(46, 50, '5', '0', 'Function Follows Forum', '', '', '', 'The annual gathering of great design minds in Hong Kong â€“ and the gala dinner for the Hong Kong Design Awards at the end of it â€“ is one of the highlights of Asiaâ€™s design calendar.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;The annual gathering of great design minds in Hong Kong &amp;ndash; and the gala dinner for the Hong Kong Design Awards at the end of it &amp;ndash; is one of the highlights of Asia&amp;rsquo;s design calendar.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	For a week in late November and early December this year, some of the world&amp;rsquo;s greatest designers and most insightful business leaders will gather in Hong Kong for the tenth edition of Business of Design Week. This year&amp;rsquo;s partner country is Germany &amp;ndash; a design leader if there ever was one. With one eye to the past and another to the future, we talked to six of BODW&amp;rsquo;s most exciting speakers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Nosigner&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Product Designer, Japan&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/46/function_follows_forum1.jpg_135039_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What he&amp;rsquo;s working on right now: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	A top-secret collaboration with a Japanese company. He also recently finished the Moon Light, an LED lamp inspired by the full moon.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What he&amp;rsquo;ll be doing at BODW:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Talking about the OLIVE project, an online design platform that provided useful solutions to survivors of the Tohoku earthquake. &amp;ldquo;There were more than 200 ideas and designs, such as temporary toilets, how to clean the water, different toy ideas for children to help those who were victims.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What he was doing when BODW was launched in 2001:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Still a student. &amp;ldquo;I studied architectural design and I wanted to become an architect,&amp;rdquo; he says, but his curiosity about the relationship between &amp;ldquo;architecture and space and humans&amp;rdquo; led him to experiment with broader design projects.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Why he&amp;rsquo;s looking forward to BODW:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;You learn about new topics or address important topics such as the ecosystem of design, the possibility of design from many point of views. You get to meet different designers, exhibitors and I really look forward to meeting my fans. You also get to meet new friends and see the relationships between different countries.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;His design philosophy:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;I believe that design can be done by everyone, even those who are not designers, but people or human beings, as they already have the instinct to edit the values. I believe that this point of view is really important, because everything can be changed at this age.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;One of Germany&amp;rsquo;s greatest contributions to global design:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The Porsche 911. &amp;ldquo;It is the only car icon whose design language and composition was inherited 50 years without change from the beginning,&amp;rdquo; he says.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;His impression of Hong Kong&amp;rsquo;s design scene?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;Design culture in Hong Kong is very young. The history of design is mature in Japan but Hong Kong has room for expansion due to its developing design force.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Anthony Lo&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Designer for Renault, France&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/46/function_follows_forum2.jpg_135056_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 204px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What he&amp;rsquo;s working on right now:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	25 projects in total, including six concept cars based around milestones, emotions and experiences in human life: love, exploration, family, work, play and wisdom.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What he&amp;rsquo;ll be doing at BODW:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Talking about Renault&amp;rsquo;s involvement in motorsports and electric vehicles. &amp;ldquo;Renault is one of the very few companies that is very committed to electric vehicles. Altogether, we will soon have a four-car range of electric vehicles.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;The hardest thing about designing cars:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Not only is there a lead time of three years &amp;ndash; &amp;ldquo;if you follow what&amp;rsquo;s in fashion, the trend will have passed by the time you finish the car&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; safety is always a paramount concern. &amp;ldquo;Most designers don&amp;rsquo;t have to worry about what happens when their product is involved in a crash.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/46/function_follows_forum3.jpg_135113_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What he was doing when BODW was launched in 2001:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Working for General Motors in Sweden, where he was asked to analyse the design strengths and weaknesses of Saab. &amp;ldquo;I was asked to create a new design for the brand based on heritage and where they came from. This new look that we created became the look of the current products.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Why he&amp;rsquo;s looking forward to BODW:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;There are no comparable conferences. I&amp;rsquo;m curious about what some of my counterparts in other car companies will be taking about. What I find difficult is that as designers we love to talk about what we do, but we can&amp;rsquo;t because of confidentiality issues. It&amp;rsquo;s a dilemma.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;One of Germany&amp;rsquo;s greatest contributions to global design:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;I have lived in Germany twice, once in 1990 and the second time in 2006, and I really appreciate the high standard people set in everyday life. Because of that, if you look at the car industry, car companies in Germany are leading the global car development. Everyone is using Germany as a benchmark.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;His impression of Hong Kong&amp;rsquo;s design scene:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Although he has spent his entire working life outside of Hong Kong, he credits his studies at the Hong Kong Polytechnic University for laying the foundation for his success. &amp;ldquo;Without that, it wouldn&amp;rsquo;t have been so smooth.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;He Jian-ping&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Graphic designer, Germany&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/46/function_follows_forum4.jpg_135129_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What he&amp;rsquo;s working on right now:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	One by One, a book introducing 628 graphic designers from 47 countries. &amp;ldquo;I hope this publication can reflect the current situation of graphic design, to speak up for graphic designers, and to promote and encourage the creative industry, not to continue its depression caused by the development of technology.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What he&amp;rsquo;ll be doing at BODW:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Working with Freeman Lau and Amy Chow on De Sein &amp;ndash; German Graphic Design from Postwar to Present, which will include posters, publications and visual identity projects.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What he was doing when BODW was launched in 2001:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	He had just graduated from the Berlin University of the Arts. &amp;ldquo;Back then my designs were mainly posters for the university activities and events.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Why he&amp;rsquo;s looking forward to BODW:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;I think design and business are similar to Yin and Yang.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;One of Germany&amp;rsquo;s greatest contributions to global design:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Bauhaus. &amp;ldquo;Its design concepts changed the environment and society where we live, or I should say, it changed the quality of living. The architectural construction of glass frames and structures, criteria in typesetting, the applications of lowercase letters, photographic experiment and montages. In furniture design there was the application of straight and clean silhouettes.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;His impression of Hong Kong&amp;rsquo;s design scene:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;Hong Kong is a small land with a lot of people, so design is essential. I think the popularity of design in Hong Kong and its government&amp;rsquo;s effort in promotion is satisfactory. As least, as an observer, I think it&amp;rsquo;s not bad. Vivien Tam, Shanghai Tang, Alan Chan are some of the good examples of designers from Hong Kong who gained their recognition from the world. I think they are great.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Kai-Yin Lo&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/46/function_follows_forum5.jpg_135155_vino_cms_.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Historian and jewellery designer, Hong Kong&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What she&amp;rsquo;s working on right now:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Her most recent project was a series of ceramics for Hong Kong&amp;rsquo;s Hotel ICON, inspired by ceramics from the Song Dynasty, which ruled China 1,000 years ago. &amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s a great dynasty. The height of Chinese civilization and refinement.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/46/function_follows_forum6.jpg_135211_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What she&amp;rsquo;ll be doing at BODW:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Speaking about her work in the context of heritage in design, including her use of Buddhist knots, which can be found in art and decor all along the former Silk Road, from China to the Middle East. &amp;ldquo;It was part of the Chinese design language that spread through textiles, wood carving, mosaics and that travelled all the way to Europe.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What she was doing when BODW was launched in 2001:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Designing jewellery and working on the first of her five books, a collection of articles on furniture that is often used as a teaching resource in design schools.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Why she&amp;rsquo;s looking forward to BODW:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;There are the keynote speakers, and they draw because of their name, but when you listen to them, you see why they are what they are. It is a wonderful opportunity to see the world&amp;rsquo;s great masters sharing their thoughts and work with you. It&amp;rsquo;s eye-opening.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/46/function_follows_forum7.jpg_135234_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;One of Germany&amp;rsquo;s greatest contributions to global design:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;Things that work, from cars to implements. What I found was that the studios in Germany of the leading designers are not big. These people who have such influential outreach operate on relatively small scales.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Her impression of Hong Kong&amp;rsquo;s design scene: &amp;ldquo;We don&amp;rsquo;t have enough platforms. We need patrons, we need platforms. I really feel that if enterprises stressed design more, we could aim for the next stage of development. At the moment a lot of [designers] seek work elsewhere.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Annemarie Jaegi&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Director of the Bauhaus Archive, Germany&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/46/function_follows_forum8.jpg_135247_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What she&amp;rsquo;s working on right now:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Exploring the impact of Bauhaus, &amp;ldquo;the most important school of architecture, design and art of the 20th century.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What she&amp;rsquo;ll be doing at BODW:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Speaking about the Bauhaus Archive. &amp;ldquo;[It] is not only a place for the history of design, it also acts as a forum for contemporary themes from the world of the arts &amp;ndash; like the Bauhaus in its own time.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;What she was doing when BODW was launched in 2001:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;I am an art historian, and at that time I was teaching as a professor at the University of Karlsruhe in Germany.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Why she&amp;rsquo;s looking forward to BODW:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;I am very concerned in the exchange with young and established international designers. BODW in Hong Kong is a very vivid place. I would like to meet people from the design scene and discover new design trends from Asia.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/46/function_follows_forum9.jpg_135302_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;One of Germany&amp;rsquo;s greatest contributions to global design:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;The Bauhaus and the Hochschule f&amp;uuml;r Gestaltung Ulm [Ulm School of Design] had a very strong impact on functional design. Germany is still known for its fusion of aesthetics and technology in the process of product development. The understanding that aesthetics and technique have to be unified has spread globally. The lesson might be that you have to be open-minded, learn by experimenting and regard social needs and developments if you want to create products or services which are important for today and have a sustainable effect for the future.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Her impression of Hong Kong&amp;rsquo;s design scene:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	This will be her first visit. &amp;ldquo;But the Business of Design Week is known as one of the most important Asian brand and design conference,&amp;rdquo; so she has high hopes.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Christopher DeWolf', '2012-03-01', '10:02:37', '2012-02-27', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '13:43', '201202271343', '46_small__095034_vino_cms_.jpg', '46_medium__095034_vino_cms_.jpg', '46_big__095034_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 28, 1, 0, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-5-0-2012-02-28/', 'function-follows-forum.html', '', '', 46, ''),
(47, 24, '2', '4', 'High Life', '', '', '', 'A busy bachelor works with a designer friend to turn a Hong Kong box into a green eco-apartment to be proud of.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;span style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Photos by &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;Manyi Choi&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;A busy bachelor works with a designer friend to turn a Hong Kong box into a green eco-apartment to be proud of.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/47/high_life1.jpg_152916_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	In Hong Kong&amp;rsquo;s newest hip neighbourhood, Sai Ying Pun, a globe-trotting expat has made a home that brings together smart use of space and sustainable strategies. The unusually quiet street is lined with local shops and businesses as well as a few historic structures from the city&amp;rsquo;s British Colonial history, and while it&amp;rsquo;s not exactly in the centre of the city, Scott Clotworthy&amp;rsquo;s new property enjoys a lack of height and density that is quite rare in today&amp;rsquo;s Hong Kong. The 35-year-old cameraman&amp;rsquo;s renovated one bedroom, 38sqm home takes full advantage of the flat&amp;rsquo;s original wall-to-wall balcony with direct views of the island&amp;rsquo;s iconic Victoria Harbour. Originally from New Zealand, where even the densest cities are far greener and more spacious than his new home city, Clotworthy made sure that he and his architect and close friend, Rowena Gonzales, a principal of Hong Kong design office Liquid, made the balcony with its views over the site&amp;rsquo;s low density surroundings, into the home&amp;rsquo;s main highlight in line with their shared interest in sustainable living with a strong indoor/ outdoor relationship.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/47/high_life2.jpg_152947_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	As is typical of most homes in Hong Kong, the original apartment was what Clotworthy calls a &amp;ldquo;box-in-a building&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; namely, a space with tiny square footage and too many rooms &amp;ndash; there used to be three bedrooms where there is now only one. Clotworthy and Liquid immediately gutted the spaces to start afresh, and when they had a blank slate, the ideas began to flow.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Clotworthy is a bachelor who is often out of town with his work as a photojournalist, so his needs are quite simple. He needed a space that was flexible for all types of storage, was low maintenance, with a good spatial flow to allow the hosting of guests. He explains that he often has friends who visit or use the space when he is away, but when he is back in Hong Kong, the home has to feel like it is spacious and open enough to entertain. One of his main requirements was to have a combined entertainment centre embedded neatly within a wall. Rowena saw this as an opportunity to create a divider through the middle of the space that would have the dual purpose of holding the entertainment centre and wardrobe on either side, and become a visual divider, separating the home&amp;rsquo;s living room and bedroom into two distinct zones.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/47/high_life3.jpg_153025_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The two-rooms-in-one-space concept allows both areas to share one balcony. Each room connects to the balcony, but has access via independent sliding screens, so the bedroom can be closed to the outside, while the living room is open to it. In terms of cooling, the unit faces north, diminishing the impact that direct sunlight would have on the space. Strategically located ceiling fans in the kitchen and the master bedroom aid in the passive cooling of the home when all sliding screens are open, which enables a natural breeze in the whole space. This is rare in Hong Kong, where airconchoked apartments with no relationship to the outside world predominate.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Other sustainable features include a directional drop-down ceiling that runs the length of the home&amp;rsquo;s public area from the entrance dining area, across the living room, to the balcony outside. This drop ceiling repurposes the flat&amp;rsquo;s original parquet flooring as a feature finish, and is used to conceal spot and recessed lighting treatments, giving this public zone a feeling of added height and a bit of design flare at the same time. Other visible eco-features include the bamboo flooring, which Clotworthy says it was a great investment, because the material is made from a renewable source, but with a texture and strength that &amp;ldquo;looks and feels great&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	An extensive green wall-planting system lines the balcony&amp;rsquo;s balustrade wall, with locally-sourced plant species picked out by the designer, Gonzales. To water the green wall, Gonzales and her team designed a rainwater catchment system outside the unit, so that water naturally irrigates the soil and then flows down and through into a trough underneath the balcony&amp;rsquo;s timber deck. To save on water usage and electricity, Gonzales installed a series of low-flow fixtures in the kitchen and bathroom and convinced Clotworthy to invest in a Master Switch system that allows all the electricity in the flat to be switched off after he has left the house (except for the fridge).&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;3&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/47/high_life4.jpg_153109_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Clotworthy is pleased with the home&amp;rsquo;s transformation. He is able to have a unit that fits him aesthetically and conceptually, since the home is underpinned by green and energy-saving features. &amp;ldquo;Selecting a space can be difficult and it can be quite demoralising when you see what your money buys you in Hong Kong,&amp;rdquo; says Clotworthy of his renovation experience. &amp;ldquo;Ultimately the total cost was 20 percent higher than initially budgeted, so it was a great advantage to have the designers present options for materials. I knew that Liquid would only suggest materials that were environmentally sound and it saved me a lot of time finding materials on my own. The floor selection is a good example &amp;ndash; I wanted to explore some less expensive options, but after looking at the bamboo Rowena presented to me, it was clear that her choice was by far the best choice.&amp;rdquo; He stresses that clients should really take advantage of their partnership with their designer, and rely less on the contractor. &amp;ldquo;If you are buying and sourcing your own fittings,&amp;rdquo; says Clotworthy, &amp;ldquo;you should be able to negotiate at least 10 percent discount off everything.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'JJ Acuna', '2012-02-28', '14:13:27', '2012-02-27', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '15:18', '201202271518', '47_small__141327_vino_cms_.jpg', '47_medium__141327_vino_cms_.jpg', '47_big__141327_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 18, 1, 0, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-2-4-2012-02-28/', 'high-life.html', '', '', 47, ''),
(48, 613, '6', '13', 'Material Matters', '', '', '', 'Bamboo, paper, stone â€“ these natural and sustainable building materials all lend themselves brilliantly to home construction. We take a look at some of the most exciting residential work being done with these materials.', '', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Bamboo, paper, stone &amp;ndash; these natural and sustainable building materials all lend themselves brilliantly to home construction. We take a look at some of the most exciting residential work being done with these materials.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Bamboo&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	As a building material, bamboo is almost too good to be true. Not only does it take just four years to mature, compared with nearly half a century for trees, but a single acre of bamboo can remove 40 tonnes of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere every year. And with a tensile strength equivalent to the strongest timber, it has been used as a construction material for hundreds of years, propping up bridges and serving as a flexible, lightweight frame for houses in earthquake- prone areas.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/48/material_matters_bamboo_haouse.jpg_111856_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Not only is the entire house made of bamboo, from floor to ceiling, bamboo is the main material used in its furniture.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Though a single harvested stalk of bamboo can serve a variety of purposes &amp;ndash; everything from construction scaffolding to laundry-drying &amp;ndash; it becomes even handier when it is cut and laminated into planks, which can replace timber, brick or concrete in many situations. That&amp;rsquo;s a good thing: it takes just 70 hectares of bamboo to build 1,000 houses, compared to 600 hectares of trees, and processing bamboo uses one-eighth the energy of making concrete.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Around one billion people are believed to live in bamboo houses around the world, mainly in informal, hand-built structures in countries like Bangladesh. But architects around the world are studying ways to build even more sophisticated bamboo structures. In the south-western Chinesemcity of Kunming, one Hong Kong firm, the Oval Partnership, has recently completed the world&amp;rsquo;s first multistory bamboo house. Rising over two floors on a lush hillside, the house&amp;rsquo;s frame, walls, floors and ceiling are made entirely from laminated bamboo, along with most of its furniture.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The house&amp;rsquo;s design emphasises clean lines and smooth surfaces, with a few stylish nods to bamboo&amp;rsquo;s natural form, as in a bookcase whose frame recalls the form, if not the texture, of wild bamboo stalks. &amp;ldquo;We wanted to create a whole bamboo lifestyle to persuade people that a bamboo house doesn&amp;rsquo;t have to be rough,&amp;rdquo; says Oval Partnership director Christopher Law. &amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s much warmer than concrete. More human.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	There are other advantages, too. Bamboo provides much greater insulation than the thin slabs of concrete used to build housing in most of Asia. Its use isn&amp;rsquo;t limited to single-family homes, either: Law says that, with a steel frame, bamboo buildings could rise up to nine stories. That will come in handy as China&amp;rsquo;s urban areas grow by up to 500 million people over the next several decades.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	There&amp;rsquo;s just one problem: no building code for bamboo currently exists in any Asian country, which makes it difficult to build bamboo structures on a large scale. &amp;ldquo;There are a lot of obstacles, but eventually we will get there,&amp;rdquo; says Law. &amp;ldquo;This is the first time in more than a hundred years that we&amp;rsquo;ve found a new way to build with an entirely sustainable material. We can&amp;rsquo;t stop.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/48/material_matters_paper1.jpg_111907_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Shigeru Ban&amp;rsquo;s Paper House, built in 1995, was the world&amp;rsquo;s first (and so far only) permanent house made from paper.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Paper&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Paper is delicate, light, ethereal; its use in architecture tends to reinforce these qualities, as with the shoji, the translucent paper walls found in mJapanese houses. But it can also be surprisingly strong &amp;ndash; and it wasn&amp;rsquo;t until architect Shigeru Ban began working with paper that it became clear just how strong it could be. By rolling cardboard into tubes, Ban has been able to create a multitude of structures out of paper, including houses, art galleries, concert halls and even a cathedral.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;5&quot; cellspacing=&quot;10&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/48/material_matters_paper2.jpg_111929_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ban used paper tubes to create temporary log houses for earthquake victims in Turkey&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	We need to get rid of material prejudices,&amp;rdquo; Ban has said. &amp;ldquo;I don&amp;rsquo;t develop many new materials. I usually use existing material differently.&amp;rdquo; He first started experimenting with gluestrengthened, waterproofed paper tubes in the late 1980s. It turns out that exposure to sun and wind actually strengthens the tubes by hardening them over time. After an earthquake devastated the Japanese city of Kobe in 1995, Ban sprang into action by designing a simple one-room house for survivors that had a foundation made from beer crates, paper tube walls and tent fabric for a roof. Each house looked like a log cabin and cost less than US$2,000 to build.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The same year, Ban completed the world&amp;rsquo;s first freestanding permanent paper house, an ostentatiously spare S-shaped structure supported by 110 paper tubes. It remains the only permanent residential structure that Ban has made from paper; most of his work since then has focused on temporary housing for disaster victims and ceremonial structures like festival pavilions and concert halls, including a proposal for the reconstruction of the Christchurch Cathedral in New Zealand, which was heavily damaged in an earthquake this year. But there&amp;rsquo;s no reason why paper couldn&amp;rsquo;t be used more extensively for everyday structures. &amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s much cheaper than wood,&amp;rdquo; said Ban, &amp;ldquo;and it&amp;rsquo;s available almost everywhere. It&amp;rsquo;s also very pretty.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Stone&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;5&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/48/material_matters_stone2.jpg_111957_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 286px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Mountain Retreat is made from locallyquarried schist clad on a reinforced concrete structure.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Over thousands of years, one material has proven its ability to withstand the winds of time: stone. Think of the Giza pyramids, the Usuki Buddhas or the web of ancient walls covering the Irish countryside &amp;ndash; all are made of stone. It seems only natural that something formed over millions of years could be singularly durable.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Stone&amp;rsquo;s use in architecture is simple and straightforward. Quarried from the earth, it is cut and then assembled with cement or lime to hold the pieces together. Once a stone structure is completed, it requires relatively little maintenance. It is also a firm barrier to the outside world, protecting interiors from intense heat and bitter cold. As labour costs have increased over the past century, however, stone construction has become prohibitively expensive. Stone is now most commonly used to clad a concrete structure.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The effect is often chintzy, but that doesn&amp;rsquo;t always have to be the case. In the Southern Lakes area of New Zealand&amp;rsquo;s Otago region, locally-quarried schist bedrock, which is easy to split and stack, has long been used as a building material. &amp;ldquo;It has become almost clich&amp;eacute;d now,&amp;rdquo; with stone slapped onto fa&amp;ccedil;ades for tradition&amp;rsquo;s sake more than anything else, says architect Jeff Fearon. So when Fearon&amp;rsquo;s firm was commissioned to design an alpine retreat near Queenstown, he opted to use the schist in a far more thoughtful way.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;table align=&quot;right&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;3&quot; cellspacing=&quot;5&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://dwellasiamag.com/filemodul/news/file_itemlampiran/48/material_matters_stone.jpg_111942_vino_cms_.jpg &quot; style=&quot;width: 190px; height: 127px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;\r\n				&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n					&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:10px;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The schist cladding helps insulate the house and integrates it with the surrounding rocky landscape.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n			&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	The result is Mountain Retreat, a 100sqm house that emerges from the mountains around Lake Wakatipu with all the force and presence of a rock outcropping. Built mostly with reinforced concrete -- the surrounding area is an active seismic zone &amp;ndash; the lowslung, angular house is clad in 50 centimetres of rough-cut stone that blends into a landscape of crushed scree. Inside, sandblasted concrete walls and a simple open layout focus attention on huge picture windows with a view of the lake and surrounding beech forest. &amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s essentially a viewing platform,&amp;rdquo; says Fearon.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify; &quot;&gt;\r\n	Fearon uses stone in many of his projects and with the Mountain Retreat, it&amp;rsquo;s easy to see why. He describes it as a &amp;ldquo;multi-layered system&amp;rdquo; that works with the reinforced concrete structure to gives the house extra protection against the outside elements, especially since the site is not exposed to much sunlight in the winter. There&amp;rsquo;s also something to be said for the reassuring nature of stone. &amp;ldquo;Even though it comes at a premium, the old qualities of stone still stands strong &amp;ndash; it doesn&amp;rsquo;t go anywhere,&amp;rdquo; says Fearon.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', 'Christopher DeWolf', '2012-03-01', '09:36:47', '2012-02-28', '9999-12-30', '00:00', '11:12', '201202281112', '48_small__093647_vino_cms_.jpg', '48_medium__093647_vino_cms_.jpg', '48_big__093647_vino_cms_.jpg', '', '', 0, 0, 10, 1, 0, 3, 3, 'filemodul/news/file_item-6-13-2012-03-01/', 'material-matters.html', '', '', 48, '');
